text: Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 16B, also known as LHON (Leber's hereditary optic neuropathy), is a genetic disorder that affects the mitochondria of cells. It causes damage to the optic nerve, which can result in vision loss and other neurological symptoms. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder. It is caused by mutations in the POLG2 gene on chromosome 17q23.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 17 (MDDS17) is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by childhood onset of encephalopathy, stroke-like episodes, lactic acidosis, hypocitrullinemia, and multiple mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies. The disease has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the MRM2 gene on chromosome 7p22.3. The phenotype is similar to MELAS syndrome.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 18 is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by early onset progressive weakness, atrophy of the distal limb muscles, and multiple mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation deficiencies that have a material basis in homozygous mutation in the SLC25A21 gene on chromosome 14q11.3. It has been defined by OMIM as 618811.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 19 (MDDS19) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which means that it is passed down through generations by inheritance and can affect people who have two copies of the faulty gene. The SLC25A10 gene on chromosome 17q25.3 encodes for an essential mitochondrial protein called copper-zinc superoxide dismutase 1 (CuZnSOD), which is involved in protecting cells from oxidative stress. Mutations in this gene can lead to a decrease in CuZnSOD levels, which may result in the accumulation of harmful free radicals and damage to mitochondrial DNA. This can ultimately lead to a variety of symptoms and health problems, including developmental regression, lethargy, hypotonia, respiratory distress, and lactic acidosis.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 19 is also known as MDDS19, and it has a material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC25A10 gene on chromosome 17q25.3. It is defined by its mitochondrial DNA depletion, which can be detected through genetic testing.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 19 has a classification of OMIM:618972.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 20, also known as MNGIE type, is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple systems in the body. It is caused by a combination of two different mutations in the LIG3 gene on chromosome 17q12. This leads to a significant reduction in mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA), which results in various symptoms such as neurogastrointestinal encephalopathy, severe gastrointestinal dysmotility, neurogenic bladder, muscle weakness and atrophy, headaches, stroke-like episodes, seizures, pyramidal signs, and learning difficulties or cognitive decline. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, meaning that it requires the presence of two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Xanthinuria type I is a form of xanthinuria, which is characterized by the absence or deficiency of functioning xanthine dehydrogenase. This condition can be caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the XDH gene located on chromosome 2p23. The term "XAN1" is often used as an exact synonym for this type of xanthinuria.

Xanthinuria type II, also known as XAN2, is a type of xanthinuria characterized by deficiency of xanthine dehydrogenase and aldehyde oxidase due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MOCOS gene on chromosome 18q12.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 70, also known as SPG70 and autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 70, is a type of hereditary disorder that affects motor function. It is characterized by an infantile onset of motor delay and difficulties walking due to spasticity of the lower limbs. The condition has a material basis in compound heterozygous mutations in the MARS1 gene located on chromosome 12q13.3.<|end|>

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 79a, also known as SPG79A or autosomal dominant spastic paraplegia 79A, is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia characterized by slowly progressive cerebellar or sensory ataxia and spasticity of the lower limbs. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the UCHL1 gene on chromosome 4p13.

Hereditary spastic paraplegia 88, also known as SPG88 and autosomal dominant spastic paraplegia 88, is a genetic disorder that affects movement and can cause weakness in the lower limbs. It is caused by a mutation in the KPNA3 gene on chromosome 13q14.2. The condition has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and often starts during infancy or early childhood, with varying degrees of severity.
Hereditary spastic paraplegia 89 is a type of autosomal recessive disease.

Mitochondrial Complex V (ATP synthase) Deficiency, Nuclear Type 4a is a rare genetic disorder that affects mitochondria, the powerhouses of the cell. It is caused by a deficiency in one of the five complexes within the ATP synthase enzyme. This specific type of deficiency is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that if one parent has the gene for this disorder, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit it. The symptoms of this disorder begin in infancy and may include poor feeding and failure to thrive, developmental delay, and movement abnormalities. However, some cases may resolve spontaneously or progress slowly over time. It is also known as MC5DN4A.

Mitochondrial complex V (ATP synthase) deficiency nuclear type 4b is a rare genetic disorder that affects the mitochondria, which are responsible for producing energy in cells. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that to develop the disease, a person must inherit two copies of the faulty gene, one from each parent.
The condition typically presents at birth with symptoms such as horizontal and vertical nystagmus (involuntary eye movements), abnormal primitive reflexes, and tonus dysregulation. As the disease progresses, it can lead to fatal encephalopathy, or brain damage.
It is important to note that this disorder has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, meaning that it exists due to the transmission of genetic information from one generation to another. Additionally, the condition has its onset during congenital onset, which means it begins at birth or before birth.
The term "mitochondrial complex V (ATP synthase) deficiency nuclear type 4b" refers specifically to this disorder and is used to describe it when communicating with medical professionals. The abbreviation MC5DN4B is also used to refer to this condition, and it can be found in the Online Mendelian Inheritance in Man (OMIM) database, which is a comprehensive catalog of inherited diseases.

Mitochondrial complex V (ATP synthase) deficiency nuclear type 5, also known as MC5DN5, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is caused by homozygous mutation in the ATP5F1D gene on chromosome 19p13.3. It has exact synonyms and an exact match in OMIM (Online Mendelian Inheritance in Man).

Mitochondrial complex V (ATP synthase) deficiency, nuclear type 7 is a genetic disorder that affects the mitochondria in the body. It occurs when there is a mutation in the ATP5PO gene on chromosome 21q22.11. This leads to an imbalance in the production of energy within the mitochondria, which can cause a range of symptoms and health problems.

Mitochondrial complex V (ATP synthase) deficiency, nuclear type 7 is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that to develop the condition, a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene - one from each parent. This means that parents who are carriers of the mutated gene have a 25% chance of passing it on to each of their children.

spinocerebellar ataxia with axonal neuropathy type 3 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by onset of slowly progressive axonal peripheral neuropathy in the first decade of life, evident in distal muscle weakness and atrophy and distal sensory impairment, followed by cerebellar ataxia and atrophy that has_material_basis_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the COA7 gene on chromosome 1p32.3..

CTS1 is short for Carpal Tunnel Syndrome 1, which is a type of autosomal dominant disease. This means that it has a strong tendency to be passed down through generations in families and can affect people regardless of their own genetic makeup. It's important to note that while CTS1 has a strong genetic component, other factors such as repetitive motions and trauma can also contribute to its development. If you or someone you know is experiencing symptoms of CTS, it's always best to consult with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Carpal tunnel syndrome 2, also known as CTS2, is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the wrist and hand. It is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the COMP gene on chromosome 19p13.11. The symptoms of CTS2 include pain, weakness, and numbness in the hands and fingers, as well as reduced dexterity and grip strength. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect that you or a loved one may be experiencing these symptoms. There are several treatment options available for CTS2, including wrist splints, medications, and surgery. In some cases, early diagnosis and intervention can help to prevent long-term damage and improve recovery outcomes.

Yoon Bellen Neurodevelopmental Syndrome (YOBELN) is a rare genetic disorder that affects brain development in infants and children. It is caused by mutations in the OGDHL gene on chromosome 10q11.23. The symptoms of YOBELN can be highly variable, but often include global developmental delay, intellectual disability, seizures, hearing and visual problems, and ataxia.

Neurodevelopmental disorder with dysmorphic facies and thin corpus callosum is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder, characterized by global developmental delay, impaired intellectual development with poor or absent speech and language, dysmorphic facial features, and corpus callosum abnormalities that has_material_basis_in heterozygous mutation in the SUPT16H gene on chromosome 14q11.2. It is also known as NEDDFAC.

Chromosome 1p36 33 duplication syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects many parts of the body, including the heart and brain. It is caused by a duplication of genes on chromosome 1p36.33, specifically the ATAD3 gene cluster, which includes the ATAD3A, ATAD3B, and ATAD3C genes. This duplication leads to the fusion of these genes, causing a range of symptoms such as cardiomyopathy (heart muscle disease), corneal clouding or cataracts, hypotonia (low muscle tone), encephalopathy (brain damage), seizures, and white matter abnormalities. The disorder is usually inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a single copy of the mutated gene is enough to cause the condition. Prenatal testing can detect this syndrome, and early intervention may improve outcomes for affected individuals.

Early onset epilepsy 2, also known as EPEO2, is a type of autosomal dominant epilepsy that has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the SETD1A gene on chromosome 16p11.2. It typically presents during infancy or childhood with generalized tonic-clonic seizures.

Early-onset epilepsy 3 (EPEO3) is a type of autosomal dominant epilepsy characterized by the onset of various types of seizures during infancy or childhood, along with variable global developmental delay and intellectual disability. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the ATP6V0C gene located on chromosome 16p13.3. EPEO3 is also known as OMIM:620465.

Zaki syndrome is a genetic disorder that affects children and has several characteristic features such as developmental delay, microcephaly, short stature, dysmorphic facial features, sparse scalp hair, and other anomalies. It is caused by mutations in the WLS gene on chromosome 1p31.3. The syndrome has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the WLS gene and it is also known as Zaki Syndrome.
childhood onset neurodegeneration with brain atrophy is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

smarcb1 deficient renal medullary carcinoma is a type of renal cell carcinoma that develops in the renal medulla. It has an exact synonym of RMC, kidney medullary carcinoma, and medullary carcinoma of the kidney. It can also be referred to as medullary renal cell carcinoma or renal medullary carcinoma. It is a rare type of cancer that affects the renal medulla.

Diphthamide deficiency syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the metabolism of certain amino acids. It is caused by a deficiency in diphthamide, an amino acid derivative that plays a crucial role in protein synthesis. Symptoms typically appear during infancy and include short stature, craniofacial abnormalities, sparse hair, intellectual disability, and global developmental delay. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that both copies of the gene must be affected for the syndrome to develop. Diphthamide deficiency syndrome can also be referred to as craniofacial dysplasia-short stature-ectodermal anomalies-intellectual disability syndrome and developmental delay with short stature, dysmorphic facial features, and sparse hair.

Diphthamide deficiency syndrome 1 is a type of diphthamide deficiency syndrome. It occurs due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DPH1 gene located on chromosome 17p13.3. This condition is also known as DEDSSH1, DPH1 syndrome, Loucks-Innes syndrome, and developmental delay with short stature, dysmorphic facial features, and sparse hair 1. It has been exactely synonymized to OMIM:616901.

Diphthamide deficiency syndrome 2 is a type of diphthamide deficiency syndrome that has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DPH2 gene on chromosome 1p34.1. It is also known as developmental delay with short stature, dysmorphic facial features, and sparse hair 2. It has exact synonyms of DEDSSH2 and OMIM:620062.

Diphthamide deficiency syndrome, also known as neurodevelopmental disorder with short stature, prominent forehead, and feeding difficulties (NEDSFF), is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the absence or reduction of diphthamide, an essential amino acid that plays a crucial role in protein synthesis. People affected by this condition typically have short stature, a large forehead, feeding problems, and delayed walking abilities. The disorder is caused by mutations in the DPH5 gene located on chromosome 1p21.2. It has been described as having a phenotype of absent speech, difficulty walking, and other developmental delays. NEDSFF is also known as Diphthamide deficiency syndrome, and it has an exact synonym of NEDSFF and OMIM:620070 for reference.

Schwannomatosis 1, also known as neurofibromatosis 3 (NF3), is a type of schwannomatosis that has a genetic basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SMARCB1 gene on chromosome 22q11.23. It is characterized by the growth of multiple benign tumors, known as neurofibromas, on the nerves and peripheral nervous system.

The term "schwannomatosis" refers to a group of disorders that affect the Schwann cells, which are responsible for insulating and supporting nerve fibers in the peripheral nervous system. In addition to schwannomatosis 1, there are several other types of schwannomatosis, including:

* Schwannomatosis 2 (NF4): This type is characterized by the development of multiple cutaneous and subcutaneous neurofibromas, as well as optic nerve gliomas. It has a genetic basis in mutations in the KRAS gene on chromosome 9p21.
* Schwannomatosis 3 (NF5): This type is characterized by the development of multiple cutaneous and subcutaneous neurofibromas, as well as plexiform neurofibromas that infiltrate the skin and surrounding tissues. It has a genetic basis in mutations in the NF1 gene on chromosome 17p11.3.
* Schwannomatosis 4 (NF6): This type is characterized by the development of multiple plexiform neurofibromas that infiltrate the skin and surrounding tissues, as well as other tumors such as ependymomas and malignant peripheral nerve sheath tumors. It has a genetic basis in mutations in the LAMB3 gene on chromosome 19q13.2.
* Schwannomatosis 5 (NF7): This type is characterized by the development of multiple plexiform neurofibromas that infiltrate the skin and surrounding tissues, as well as other tumors such as malignant peripheral nerve sheath tumors. It has a genetic basis in mutations in the KIT gene on chromosome 4q12.
* Schwannomatosis 6 (NF8): This type is characterized by the development of multiple cutaneous and subcutaneous neurofibromas, as well as other tumors such as malignant peripheral nerve sheath tumors and gliomas. It has a genetic basis in mutations in the BRAF gene on chromosome 7p13.1.
* Schwannomatosis 9 (NF10): This type is characterized by the development of multiple cutaneous and subcutaneous neurofibromas, as well as other tumors such as malignant peripheral nerve sheath tumors and ependymomas. It has a genetic basis in mutations in the SMARCB1 gene on chromosome 22q11.23, the same gene that is affected in schwannomatosis 1.

It's important to note that while these different types of schwannomatosis have distinct genetic causes and clinical features, they all share a common pathway of tumorigenesis involving the activation of mutant RAS or other signaling pathways in the Schwann cells.

Schwannomatosis 2, also known as neurofibromatosis 3 (NF3), is a genetic disorder characterized by the development of multiple non-cancerous tumors called schwannomas on the nerves. It is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the LZTR1 gene on chromosome 22q11.2. These tumors can cause various symptoms, including pain, numbness, and weakness in the affected limbs, as well as problems with balance and coordination. In some cases, schwannomatosis 2 may also affect other parts of the body, such as the skin and eyes. Treatment options depend on the size and location of the tumors, but may include surgery, radiation therapy, or chemotherapy.

Spinal neurofibromatosis is a type of neurofibromatosis 1, which is characterized by the presence of multiple spinal nerve root tumors called neurofibromas. It is also known as FNS (familial spinal neurofibromatosis), SNF (spinal neurofibromatosis), and familial spinal neurofibromatosis. It has an exact match in OMIM:162210.

Watson syndrome, also known as Neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1), is a genetic disorder that affects the development of nervous system and causes various symptoms such as café-au-lait spots, tumors on nerve tissue, bone deformities, and increased risk of cancer. It is an autosomal dominant disorder which means that if one parent has the gene, there is a 50% chance of passing it on to their child. The disease is caused by a mutation in the NF1 gene located on chromosome 17q11.2.

Legius syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by multiple cafe-au-lait macules and possible skin fold freckling without neurofibromas, optic gliomas, or Lisch nodules. It has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SPRED1 gene on chromosome 15q14. It is also known as LGSS and NF1-like syndrome, among other synonyms. It has been matched with various terms such as GARD, MESH, NCI, OMIM, ORDO, SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01, and UMLS_CUI in the provided sources.

Mitochondrial Complex IV Deficiency, Nuclear Type 23, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the cytochrome c oxidase enzyme in the mitochondria. This results in a deficiency in cellular respiration and can cause various symptoms including lactic acidosis, hypotonia, seizures, developmental delay, and death. It is caused by mutations in the COX11 gene on chromosome 17q22 and has exact synonyms such as MC4DN23. The condition can be diagnosed through genetic testing and treated with supplementation of the affected enzyme and supportive care.

Parkinson's disease 25, also known as PARK25 or autosomal recessive early-onset Parkinson disease 25 with impaired intellectual development, is a type of Parkinson's disease that has a genetic basis. It is caused by mutations in the PTPA gene on chromosome 9q34.11. The severity of symptoms can vary from mild to moderately impaired intellectual development. It is important for individuals with this condition to seek medical attention and receive proper treatment.

Dopamine transporter deficiency syndrome (DTDS) is a rare genetic disorder characterized by movement symptoms, such as tremors, bradykinesia, and dystonia. It is caused by mutations in the SLC6A3 gene on chromosome 5p15.33. The exact synonym for DTDS is "DTD."

Atypical dopamine transporter deficiency syndrome is a condition characterized by a lack of function in the dopamine transporter protein. This can lead to symptoms such as movement disorders, including Parkinson's disease and dystonia, as well as cognitive and psychiatric issues. It can have onset in both childhood and adulthood, but typically presents with different symptoms depending on the age of onset. The condition has a genetic basis and is often inherited from one or both parents.

Classic dopamine transporter deficiency syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by infantile onset of chorea, dystonia, ballismus, and orolingual dyskinesia followed by progressive parkinsonism-dystonia. It has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC6A3 gene on chromosome 5p15.33. Another distinct feature is an elevated homovanillic acid to hydroxyindoleacetic acid ratio in cerebrospinal fluid. It has exact synonyms such as PKDYS1, classic DTDS, infantile parkinsonism-dystonia 1, and OMIM:PS613135. It also has broader match with other conditions, including MESH:C567730, NCI:C129866, and ORDO:238455. Finally, it is also known by the exact match SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01:722763000 and UMLS_CUI:C2751067.

Infantile Parkinsonism-Dystonia 2 (PKDYS2) is a type of movement disorder that is characterized by a combination of symptoms including parkinsonism, dystonia, poor fine motor skills, and autonomic dysfunction such as abnormal sweating, cold extremities, and poor sleep. It is caused by mutations in the SLC18A2 gene located on chromosome 10q25.3. This condition has been referred to as Brain dopamine-serotonin vesicular transport disease and PKDYS2.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 1 (MC4DN1) is a form of autosomal recessive mitochondrial disease. It's also known as Cox deficiency and benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy. MC4DN1 has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SURF1 gene on chromosome 9q34.2. The exact synonym for this condition is MC4DN1, and it can be matched to NCI:C176895, OMIM:220110, and UMLS_CUI:C5435656.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 3 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the mitochondria in the body. It is caused by a mutation in the COX10 gene on chromosome 17p12. This condition is characterized by a deficiency of Complex IV, which results in impaired oxidative phosphorylation and can lead to symptoms such as muscle weakness, fatigue, and lactic acidosis. The condition is also known as benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy and has an exact synonym of MC4DN3. It is important to note that this disease has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the COX10 gene on chromosome 17p12.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 4 (MC4DN4) is a form of mitochondrial disease that results from the failure of the fourth complex in the electron transport chain. This complex is also known as CII or Complex II. It is responsible for transferring electrons from UTP to FADH2 and producing a proton gradient, which is used to drive ATP synthesis.

MC4DN4 is an autosomal recessive disorder, meaning that it requires the inheritance of two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) for the disease to develop. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SCO1 gene on chromosome 17p13.1.

MC4DN4 is characterized by lactic acidosis, which occurs due to a buildup of lactate in the blood and tissues. This can lead to symptoms such as weakness, lethargy, and poor feeding in infants. As the disease progresses, it can cause muscle weakness, cramping, and atrophy. MC4DN4 is also associated with developmental delays, seizures, and hearing loss.

Treatment options for MC4DN4 may include dietary modifications, such as avoiding high-energy foods and opting for a low-carbohydrate diet to reduce lactate production. Other treatments may be necessary in more severe cases or when symptoms become life-threatening. It is important to consult with a medical professional for a proper diagnosis and treatment plan.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 7, also known as MC4DN7, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the mitochondria in the body. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the faulty gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Mitochondrial complex IV is responsible for producing adenosine triphosphate (ATP), which is the energy source for cells in the body. When there is a deficiency in this complex, it can lead to a range of symptoms and issues, including fatigue, muscle weakness, and even heart failure in severe cases.

MC4DN7 affects predominantly the skeletal and smooth muscles, as well as the heart. It is often diagnosed in infancy or early childhood and can cause short stature and developmental delays if not treated properly. Treatment typically involves a combination of medications, dietary changes, and exercise therapy to help manage symptoms and improve energy levels.

It's important to note that while MC4DN7 has a genetic basis, it is relatively rare, and most people with the condition have a normal life expectancy when treated properly. However, as with any medical condition, early diagnosis and treatment are crucial for the best possible outcomes.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 8 is a rare genetic disorder that affects the mitochondria in the body. Mitochondria are responsible for producing energy and when they do not function properly, it can lead to a variety of health problems. In this particular condition, there is a defect in the fourth complex of the mitochondrial electron transport chain, which results in decreased production of ATP. This can cause issues with energy production, cellular metabolism, and oxidative phosphorylation.

Symptoms of mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 8 usually begin in infancy and include gait difficulties, spasticity, dysarthria, hypotonia, and variable intellectual disability. As the condition progresses, it can lead to more severe neurological symptoms such as ataxia, epilepsy, and blindness.

Diagnosis is typically made through genetic testing, which can identify mutations in the TACO1 gene on chromosome 17q23.3. Treatment options are limited and focused on managing symptoms rather than curing the condition. This may include physical therapy, speech therapy, medications to control seizures or muscle spasticity, and nutritional support. It is important for those affected by this condition to work closely with a medical team to develop an individualized treatment plan tailored to their specific needs.

mitochondrial complex iv deficiency nuclear type 10 is a rare genetic disorder that affects the mitochondria in the body. It is caused by a mutation in the COX14 gene on chromosome 12q13.12, which leads to a deficiency of Complex IV in the electron transport chain. This results in reduced production of ATP, which can lead to various symptoms such as muscle weakness, fatigue, and poor exercise performance. It is also known as COX deficiency, benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy, and has exact synonyms like MC4DN10 and OMIM:619053.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 11 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the functioning of the mitochondria in the body. It is characterized by a lack of Complex IV activity in the mitochondria, which can lead to a variety of symptoms and health issues.

The exact synonym for this condition is MC4DN11, and it can be matched to OMIM:619054 and UMLS_CUI:C5436694.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 12 is a rare genetic disorder that affects the energy-producing mitochondria in the body. It is caused by a mutation in the PET100 gene located on chromosome 19p13.2. This condition leads to a deficiency of Complex IV, which is responsible for oxidizing cytochrome c and producing ATP (adenosine triphosphate), a molecule that provides energy to the cell.

It's important to note that mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 12 is a rare condition, and more research is needed to better understand it and its implications for affected individuals and their families.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 14, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the mitochondria in the body. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means it is inherited from both parents and can cause serious health problems if both copies of the gene are affected. The disorder is caused by mutations in the COA3 gene on chromosome 17q21.2. These mutations lead to a deficiency of Complex IV, which is essential for energy production in the mitochondria.

It's important to note that while researchers have identified a genetic basis for this disorder, it remains a complex disease with many unanswered questions. Further studies are needed to better understand its underlying mechanisms and to develop more effective treatments.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 15, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the mitochondria in the body. It occurs due to a mutation in the COX8A gene on chromosome 11q13.1. This leads to a decrease in the activity of Complex IV, which is responsible for the conversion of cytochrome c to oxidized form.
