In summary, mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 15 is a rare genetic disorder that affects the mitochondria in the body due to a mutation in the COX8A gene on chromosome 11q13.1. It causes a decrease in Complex IV activity and can lead to severe symptoms if left untreated. Diagnosis is made through genetic testing, and treatment involves addressing individual symptoms with various interventions.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 16 is a genetic disorder that affects the mitochondria in the body. It is caused by mutations in the COX4I1 gene on chromosome 16q24.1. This leads to a deficiency of Complex IV, which is essential for producing ATP (adenosine triphosphate) in the cell. As a result, it can cause various symptoms such as muscle weakness, fatigue, and poor growth. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person needs to inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 17 is a rare genetic disorder that affects the mitochondria in the body. The mitochondria are responsible for producing energy and this particular disorder occurs when there is a problem with the production of ATP (adenosine triphosphate), which is an essential molecule for cellular respiration. This can lead to symptoms such as muscle weakness, fatigue, and poor growth. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 18, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the mitochondria in the body. It is caused by mutations in the COX6A2 gene on chromosome 16p11.2. The condition can cause symptoms such as muscle weakness, fatigue, and poor growth, and is usually diagnosed in infancy or early childhood. Treatment may include medication to improve energy levels and support for the patient's overall health.

mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 19 is a rare genetic disorder that affects the mitochondria, which are the energy-producing structures in our cells. Specifically, it affects the fourth complex of the electron transport chain, also known as Complex IV or Coenzyme Q10 (CoQ10). This leads to a deficiency in this important coenzyme.

This condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person needs to inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder. It primarily affects infants and young children and can cause a range of symptoms, including muscle weakness, heart problems, and liver disease.

Treatment for mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 19 is focused on managing the symptoms and providing supportive care. This may include medications to help with energy production, dietary modifications to provide additional nutrients, and physical therapy to improve muscle strength. In some cases, a heart or liver transplant may be considered if the affected organ is severely damaged.

Overall, mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 19 is a serious and life-threatening condition that requires careful management by healthcare professionals experienced in treating genetic disorders.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 20 is a rare genetic disorder that affects the function of mitochondria in the body. It is caused by a mutation in the COX5A gene on chromosome 15q24.2 and presents as benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy. The disorder is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that to have full-blown symptoms, a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent). Common symptoms include muscle weakness and fatigue, which can worsen with physical activity. Diagnosis is typically made through blood tests and genetic testing. Treatment may involve medications to manage symptoms and address any underlying metabolic abnormalities.

Mitochondrial complex IV deficiency, nuclear type 21 (MC4DN21) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the mitochondria in the body. It is caused by mutations in the NDUFA4 gene, which is located on chromosome 7p21.3. This leads to a deficiency of Complex IV, also known as cytochrome c oxidase, in the mitochondria, resulting in reduced energy production and cell damage. MC4DN21 primarily affects infants and children and can cause symptoms such as muscle weakness, poor feeding, vomiting, lethargy, and failure to thrive. Diagnosis is made through genetic testing, and treatment may involve supportive care and supplementation of essential nutrients.

Mitochondrial Complex IV Deficiency, Nuclear Type 22 (MC4DN22) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the mitochondria in the body. It occurs due to a homozygous mutation in the COX16 gene on chromosome 14q24.2. This leads to a deficiency in Complex IV, which is responsible for the conversion of cytochrome c into oxidized form and protons into the matrix. As a result, it can cause benign infantile mitochondrial myopathy, characterized by muscle weakness, fatigue, and lactic acidosis. It has a material basis in homozygous mutation of COX16 gene, and is also known as MC4DN22 or OMIM:619355.

Metabolic dysfunction and alcohol associated liver disease (MASLD) is a type of steatotic liver disease characterized by at least one of the five cardiometabolic risk factors for MASLD and alcohol consumption of 140-350g/week (females) or 210-420g/week (males). This disease is distinguished from MASLD by increased alcohol consumption and from ALD by the evidence of one or more of the MASLD cardiometabolic risk factors. The exact synonyms for MASLD are MetALD and metabolic dysfunction and alcohol related liver disease.

Schinzel-Giedion syndrome (SGS) is a rare autosomal dominant ectodermal dysplasia characterized by distinctive facial features, severe developmental delay, hydronephrosis, typical skeletal malformations, genital and cardiac anomalies, and increased tumor prevalence. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the SETBP1 gene on chromosome 18q12.3. The exact synonyms for SGS include Schinzel-Giedion midface retraction syndrome (SGSMRS). SGS is also known as GARD:117, MESH:C536632, NCI:C129308, OMIM:269150 and ORDO:798. It has an exact match in SNOMEDCT_US\_2023\_03\_01:18899000 and UMLS\_CUI:C0265227.

Inflammatory poikiloderma with hair abnormalities and acral keratoses is a type of skin disease, specifically characterized by mottled hyper- and hypopigmentation of the skin, sparse scalp hair and eyelashes, sparse or absent eyebrows, and palmoplantar keratoses. It has material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is also known as LIPHAK syndrome.

Polyhydramnios megalencephaly and symptomatic epilepsy is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the presence of excess amniotic fluid (polyhydramnios), large head size (megalencephaly), and symptomatic epilepsy. It is caused by homozygous mutation in the STRADA gene on chromosome 17q23.3. The disorder has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, and it starts during fetal development. The condition has been assigned to several terms including syndrome, PMSE, PMSE syndrome, Pretzel syndrome, GARD:12913, MESH:C567020, OMIM:611087, ORDO:500533, and SNOMEDCT\_US\_2023\_03\_01:1167371007.

The term you are referring to is "Neurodevelopmental Disorder with Hypotonia and Speech Delay" which is also known as NEDHSS. It is a type of autosomal genetic disease that is characterized by global developmental delay, impaired intellectual development with poor or absent speech, and fine and gross motor delay. The EIF4A2 gene on chromosome 3q27.3 is believed to have a material basis in the inheritance of this disorder.

Neurodevelopmental disorder with dysmorphic facies and behavioral abnormalities is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the SRSF1 gene on chromosome 17q22. The exact synonym for this condition is NEDFBA, and it has an exact match in OMIM:620489.
neurodevelopmental disorder with dysmorphic facies and distal limb anomalies is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder.

Chromosome 16p11.2 deletion syndrome, also known as Proximal 16p11.2 microdeletion syndrome, is a genetic disorder characterized by language delay and mild intellectual disability. It is caused by the partial deletion of a contiguous 593-kb region of chromosome 16p11.2 (chr16:29.5-30.1 Mb). This condition has been identified as having material basis in this genetic alteration.

This syndrome is classified under the ICD10CM code Q93.5 and is considered to be a type of chromosomal deletion syndrome. It is also related to other conditions such as ICD10CM:Q93.5, GARD:10740, OMIM:611913, ORDO:261197 and UMLS_CUI:C3150154, and UMLS_CUI:C4273657.
It is important to note that this information is only a summary and for more details, consult with a medical professional or a genetic counselor.

Mitchell syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant peroxisomal disease that causes progressive episodic demyelination, sensorimotor polyneuropathy, and hearing loss. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the ACOX1 gene on chromosome 17q25.1.

Retinal macular dystrophy 2, also known as MCDR2, is a type of retinal macular dystrophy characterized by slowly progressive "bull's eye" maculopathy, mild visual impairment, and central scotomata. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the PROM1 gene on chromosome 4p15.32.

Familial multiple lipomatosis is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by the development of numerous encapsulated lipomas on the extremities and trunk. It has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The exact matches for this condition are GARD:12925, MESH:D000071070, OMIM:151900, ORDO:199276, and UMLS_CUI:C1275273.

Early onset vitamin B6 dependent epilepsy 4, also known as AASA dehydrogenase deficiency, EPEO4, PDE-ALDH7A1, antiquitin deficiency, is a type of epilepsy that is caused by mutations in the ALDH7A1 gene on chromosome 5q23.2. It is characterized by seizures that begin in early childhood and are dependent on pyridoxine (a form of vitamin B6).

Peeling skin syndrome 1, also known as PSS1, is a type of peeling skin syndrome that is caused by a homozygous mutation in the CDSN gene on chromosome 6p21.33. It has exact synonyms such as generalized inflammatory peeling skin syndrome, inflammatory peeling skin syndrome, and peeling skin syndrome type B. It is also known by the exact match terms OMIM:270300, ORDO:263553, and UMLS_CUI:C5679693.

Peeling skin syndrome 2 (PSS2) is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the peeling of skin, often starting on the hands and feet. It occurs due to mutations in the TGM5 gene located on chromosome 15q15.2. The condition can be inherited in an autosomal recessive or autosomal dominant manner. Other names for PSS2 include acral peeling skin syndrome, localized peeling skin syndrome, and ectodermal dysplasia. It is important to note that there are two types of Peeling Skin Syndrome: acral (APS) and generalised. Acral means it affects only the ends of the fingers and toes.

Peeling skin syndrome type 3, also known as PSS3 or OMIM #616265, is a rare genetic disorder caused by a mutation in the CHST8 gene on chromosome 19q13.11. It is characterized by peeling skin and other symptoms, which can vary greatly depending on the severity of the mutation. PSS3 primarily affects children and adolescents, and there is no cure at this time. However, with early diagnosis and proper treatment, many affected individuals may be able to manage their condition effectively.

It's important for parents and caregivers to be aware of the signs and symptoms of PSS3 in order to seek medical attention promptly if necessary. The disorder can lead to significant physical and emotional distress, as well as complications with growth and development. In some cases, patients may require skin grafts or other surgical interventions to address the peeling skin.

Researchers are currently working on developing new treatments for PSS3, but there is still much that is unknown about this rare condition. It's important for those affected by PSS3 and their families to receive support from healthcare professionals, as well as from organizations dedicated to helping individuals with rare diseases.

If you or someone you know may be experiencing symptoms of PSS3, it's important to seek medical attention right away. A proper diagnosis is crucial for effective treatment and management of the condition.

Peeling skin syndrome 4, also known as autosomal recessive exfoliative ichthyosis (AREI), is a type of peeling skin syndrome characterized by the presence of homozygous mutation in the CSTA gene on chromosome 3q21.1. It has broad synonyms, including exfoliative ichthyosis, ichthyosis exfoliativa, and ichthyosis bullosa of Siemens-like, and it is also known by its exact synonym, peeling skin syndrome 4 (PSS4). The MESH code for this condition is C564309, and it has been assigned an OMIM code of 607936.

Peeling skin syndrome 5 (PSS5) is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the presence of a homozygous mutation in the SERPINB8 gene located on chromosome 18q22.1. This leads to an autosomal recessive form of exfoliative ichthyosis, which is a severe and debilitating skin condition that causes the top layer of skin to peel off in sheets or large sections.

Symptoms typically begin within the first year of life and can progress rapidly, leading to significant skin damage and scarring. The disorder affects individuals from all ethnic backgrounds but is more common in certain populations. Treatment options are limited and primarily focus on managing symptoms rather than reversing the condition.

It's important to note that PSS5 is a rare genetic disorder, and while there might be some overlap with other skin conditions, it's essential to consult a healthcare professional for an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment plan.

Peeling skin syndrome type A, also known as PSS6, is a rare genetic disorder that causes the skin to become excessively dry and flaky. It is caused by mutations in the FLG2 gene on chromosome 1q21.3. Symptoms typically appear early in life and may include red or brown patches on the skin, hair loss, and nail abnormalities. Treatment options are available to manage the symptoms and improve overall quality of life.

Plack syndrome is a rare genetic skin condition that affects the palms of hands and soles of feet. It causes peeling skin, leukonychia (white spots on nails), acral punctate keratoses (small, round, wart-like growths), cheilitis (inflammation of mouth lining), and knuckle pads. The syndrome is caused by a mutation in the CAST gene located on chromosome 5q15. Plack syndrome has exact synonyms such as "peeling skin with leukonychia, acral punctate keratoses, cheilitis, and knuckle pads." It is also known by its medical name, which is "acrodermatitis continua hereditaria."

Borrelia miyamotoi disease is a type of primary bacterial infectious disease that is caused by the bacterium Borrelia miyamotoi. It is transmitted through the bites of certain species of ticks, including the blacklegged tick (Ixodes scapularis), western blacklegged tick (Ixodes pacificus), taiga tick (Ixodes persulcatus), and castor bean tick (Ixodes ricinus). The disease can cause a range of symptoms, such as fever, headache, chills, muscle pain, joint pain, asthenia, fatigue, and nausea. In some cases, the disease may relapse. It is also known by other names, including BMD and hard tick-borne relapsing fever.

cepacia syndrome is a type of opportunistic bacterial infectious disease that can cause necrotizing pneumonia, acute respiratory distress syndrome, and bacteremia. It is caused by the Burkholderia cepacia complex and can be transmitted through various means such as contact, droplet spread, vehicle-borne fomite transmission, and ingestion.

sifrim hitz weiss syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder. It is characterized by developmental delay, speech delay, mild-to-moderate intellectual disability and variable congenital anomalies in other systems. This condition has a genetic basis, specifically a heterozygous mutation in the CHD4 gene on chromosome 12p13.31. The syndrome also has synonyms such as CHD4 Neurodevelopmental Disorder, CHD4-related neurodevelopmental disorder, CHD4-related neurodevelopmental syndrome, SIFRIM-HITZ-WEISS MULTIPLE CONGENITAL ANOMALIES-MENTAL RETARDATION SYNDROME, and SIHIWES. It is also known by the exact matches in OMIM (617159) and ORDO (653712).

Foveal hypoplasia 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by foveal hypoplasia, which is decreased development or degeneration of the macula, the central part of the retina responsible for sharp, detailed vision. Additionally, individuals with Foveal hypoplasia 1 may experience decreased visual acuity, nystagmus, and lack of aniridia, which are abnormal eye movements and the absence of the iris respectively. The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the PAX6 gene on chromosome 11p13. Foveal hypoplasia 1 is also known as O'Donnell-Pappas syndrome or foveal hypoplasia-presenile cataract syndrome, and it has exact synonyms such as FVH1 and has narrow synonyms like OMIM:136520. It is also known to have narrower matches in the UMLS_CUI system.

Foveal Hypoplasia 2 is a rare genetic disorder that affects the retina and can cause vision loss. It is an autosomal recessive disease, which means it is inherited from both parents and can result in a milder form of the condition if only one parent passes on the mutated gene.
The condition is caused by mutations in the SLC38A8 gene located on chromosome 16q23.3. It leads to foveal hypoplasia, which is the underdevelopment of the central part of the retina responsible for sharp vision. This can result in decreased visual acuity and nystagmus, a condition where the eyes move rapidly back and forth.
Foveal Hypoplasia 2 may also be accompanied by optic nerve decussation defects and anterior segment dysgenesis, which are abnormalities of the optic nerve and front part of the eye respectively.
Overall, Foveal Hypoplasia 2 is a complex disorder that requires specialized care from medical professionals who can provide appropriate treatment and support to help manage its symptoms and improve quality of life for those affected by it.

Aniridia is a condition where the iris, the colored part of the eye, is missing or underdeveloped. Aniridia 1 is one type of aniridia that can be inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern, which means that if one parent has the gene for it, there's a good chance that their child will inherit the condition. It is caused by a mutation in the PAX6 gene located on chromosome 11p13. Aniridia 1 can also be associated with other ocular anomalies, such as microphthalmia (small eyes), coloboma (a hole in the eye), and cataracts. The term "aniridia" is derived from the Greek words "ana," meaning "without," and "iris," meaning "color."

Long QT Syndrome (LQTS) 16, also known as LQT16, is a type of autosomal dominant genetic disorder characterized by prolonged QT intervals and an increased risk of sudden death. It is caused by mutations in the CALM3 gene on chromosome 19q13.32. The symptoms may include syncope, cardiac arrest, and sudden death.

Arrhythmogenic Left Ventricular Cardiomyopathy (ALVC) is a type of intrinsic cardiomyopathy. It is characterized by hypokinetic, non-dilated, fibrotic or fibrofatty left ventricular myocardium and ventricular arrhythmias with a right bundle branch block pattern. The condition affects the left ventricle of the heart and does not involve the right ventricle to any significant extent. It is also known as Left Ventricular ACM (Arrhythmogenic Cardiomyopathy) and Left-dominant arrhythmogenic cardiomyopathy.

arrhythmogenic biventricular cardiomyopathy is a type of intrinsic cardiomyopathy.
arrhythmogenic biventricular cardiomyopathy has the definition An intrinsic cardiomyopathy characterized by hypokinetic, non-dilated, fibrotic or fibrofatty replacement in both the left and right ventricular myocardium, with ventricular arrhythmias with left and right bundle branch block patterns.
arrhythmogenic biventricular cardiomyopathy has an exact synonym of biventricular ACM.

Neurodevelopmental disorder with hypotonia, language delay, and skeletal defects (NEDHLSD) is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder characterized by behavioral abnormalities and developmental delay ranging from mild-to-moderate impaired intellectual development with expressive language delay to severely impaired intellectual development, severe hypotonia with delayed walking or inability to walk, and poor or absent speech. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the CACNA1C gene on chromosome 12p13.33.

Spastic tetraplegia, thin corpus callosum, and progressive microcephaly is a rare genetic disorder. It is caused by mutations in the SLC1A4 gene on chromosome 2p14. This leads to intellectual developmental delays and abnormalities in brain development such as spasticity, thin corpus callosum, and progressive microcephaly. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder. There is no cure for this condition, but early intervention and supportive care can help improve the quality of life for those affected.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual developmental disorder, Bain type is a rare genetic condition that affects brain development and causes a range of physical and mental health issues. It is characterized by delayed psychomotor development, impaired intellectual development with behavioral abnormalities, and musculoskeletal and growth abnormalities. The condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the HNRNPH2 gene on chromosome Xq22.1.
It is also known by several other names such as HNRNPH2-related neurodevelopmental disorder, MRXSB (Mental Retardation, X-linked, Syndrome, Bain Type), and GARD:13442, NCI:C183311, OMIM:300986, and UMLS_CUI:C4310814.

Muscular disease refers to a condition that affects the muscles, which is part of the musculoskeletal system. The musculoskeletal system includes bones, joints, cartilage, ligaments, tendons, and muscles. A muscular disease can result from various factors such as genetics, physical activity, or environmental exposures. Some common examples of muscular diseases include myasthenia gravis, polymyositis, dermatomyositis, and Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease. It is important to note that while these diseases can affect the muscles, they do not necessarily have a location within the muscle tissue itself.

Bone disease refers to a type of connective tissue disease that affects the structure or development of bone, or causes an impairment of normal bone function. One example of this type of disease is osteoporosis, which is characterized by a decrease in bone density and an increased risk of fractures. Other examples include arthritis, which affects the joints and can lead to pain and inflammation, and Paget's disease, which causes abnormal bone growth and repair. Bone diseases can be caused by a variety of factors, including genetics, hormonal imbalances, and certain medications.
Bone remodeling disease refers to a bone disease characterized by abnormalities in the formation or resorption of bone tissue.

Correct, bone development disease is a type of bone disease characterized by abnormal growth and development of bone or cartilage. It can occur at any age but is more common in children and young adults. There are several types of bone development diseases, including genetic disorders such as dwarfism and achondroplasia, hormonal imbalances, and certain medications. Symptoms can include short stature, bone deformities, and joint pain. Treatment options depend on the underlying cause but may involve medication, surgery, or physical therapy.

Bone deterioration disease, also known as osteoporosis, is a condition characterized by the gradual weakening and loss of bone mass. It occurs when the body fails to form new bone tissue or when existing bone tissue is reabsorbed at a faster rate than it can be replaced. This leads to an increase in the density of small gaps within the bones, making them more susceptible to fractures and other injuries. Osteoporosis typically affects older adults, but it can also occur in younger individuals with certain medical conditions or a family history of the disease. Treatment options may include medications such as bisphosphonates, calcium supplements, weight-bearing exercises, and dietary changes to promote healthy bone growth and reduce the risk of fractures.

I understand that you are trying to communicate information about ischemic bone disease. Ischemic bone disease is a type of bone disease in which the blood supply to the bone is disrupted, leading to the weakening and potential loss of bone mass. This can result in pain, fractures, and other complications if left untreated. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have ischemic bone disease or any other bone-related health issues.

I understand that you are looking for a definition or explanation of "x linked dominant disease." A x linked dominant disease is a type of X-linked monogenic disease, which refers to a single gene inheritance pattern where the mutated gene is located on the X chromosome. The term "dominant" here means that the effect of a mutation in this gene can be more severe or noticeable compared to other forms of inheritance. These diseases typically have a strong genetic component and are often inherited from a parent who carries the mutated gene but may not express it themselves.

Bone structure disease is a condition where the bones in the body do not develop properly. This can lead to abnormalities in the shape, size, and strength of the bones, which can cause various health problems. Some common symptoms of bone structure disease include pain, swelling, and limited mobility. In severe cases, it can also lead to fractures and dislocations. Bone structure diseases can be caused by a variety of factors, including genetics, nutritional deficiencies, and certain medications. Treatment for bone structure disease typically involves a combination of medication, physical therapy, and lifestyle changes to promote bone growth and prevent further damage.

Bone resorption disease, also known as osteoclastoma or reactive bone resorption, is a type of bone remodeling disease that involves the excessive breakdown and absorption of bone tissue by osteoclasts. It can lead to an abnormal decrease in bone density and mass, which can result in various health problems such as fractures, joint pain, and weakened skeletal structure. In some cases, it may also be caused or exacerbated by certain medications, medical conditions, or hormonal imbalances.

X-linked recessive disease refers to a type of genetic disorder that is passed down through the X chromosome from one generation to another. It affects both males and females, but it is more commonly seen in males due to the way the X chromosome works. A recessive gene will have less effect on an individual if they have a dominant allele (one good copy), while two non-functional alleles (no good copies) are required for a severe effect or disease to occur. This is because the other functional allele can compensate for the absence of one of the non-functional ones. Examples of X-linked recessive diseases include hemophilia, color blindness, and cystic fibrosis.

User, your statement is close but not entirely accurate. A chromosomal disease refers to a genetic disorder that is caused by abnormalities in the number or structure of chromosomes. These abnormalities can result in various health problems, including physical and mental development issues.
A common example of a chromosomal disease is Down syndrome, which occurs when an individual has three copies of chromosome 21 instead of the usual two copies. Other examples include Turner Syndrome (only one X chromosome), Klinefelter Syndrome (an extra Y chromosome), and Cri du Chat syndrome (a partial deletion of the short arm of one of the X chromosomes).
It's important to note that while these conditions have a material basis in chromosome structure variations, they are not necessarily solely dependent on those variations. Other genetic and environmental factors can also contribute to the development and expression of these diseases.

Physical disorder refers to a condition that has a material basis in genetic abnormalities, errors during embryonic development, infections or compromised intrauterine environment. It is considered as a type of disease and shares the same definition with Congenital Disorders.

Spina bifida is a type of neural tube defect, which occurs when the spine and membranes around the spinal cord do not fully develop during early fetal development. It is characterized by an incomplete closure of the spine, leading to an opening in the spinal column. This condition can cause various levels of paralysis and other health issues, depending on the location and severity of the defect. Spina bifida typically occurs more frequently in women than men and can be detected through a combination of ultrasound scans and genetic testing.

Dysbaric osteonecrosis is a type of ischemic bone disease that occurs due to nitrogen embolism, which leads to bone death. It has been defined as an ischemic bone disease with a material basis in nitrogen embolization located in the bone. The exact synonyms for dysbaric osteonecrosis include Caisson disease of bone and DON.

Metaphyseal dysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia that is characterized by abnormal bone development, resulting in broad ends on the long arm and leg bones. This condition affects the spongy inner layer of bone, causing it to enlarge. There are several synonyms for metaphyseal dysplasia, including Bakwin-Krida syndrome, Pyle's disease, and Pyle-Cohn syndrome.

Jansen's metaphyseal chondrodysplasia is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the bones, resulting in short limbs and short stature. It is caused by a mutation in the PTH receptor gene, which results in short-limbed dwarfism. The condition has several synonyms, including Jansen Disease, Jansen Metaphyseal Dysostosis, Jansen metaphyseal chondrodysplasia, and Murk Jansen Type Metaphyseal Chondrodysplasia.

Schmid metaphyseal chondrodysplasia is a type of metaphyseal dysplasia, characterized by severe short stature and bowed legs. It is also known as Japanese type spondylometaphyseal dysplasia or Schmid type metaphyseal dysplasia.

otospondylomegaepiphyseal dysplasia autosomal recessive is a type of osteochondrodysplasia that results from mutations in the COL11A2 gene, which leads to enlargement of the epiphysis in the hand and foot, distinct facial features, platyspondyly, and hearing loss. It has an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern and is also known as Nance-Insley Syndrome, Nance-Sweeney Chondrodysplasia, or OSMED.
Spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia is a type of spinal disease that results in abnormalities of bone growth located in the vertebral column, epiphysis, or metaphysis.

The spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia strudwick type is a subtype of spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia, which refers to a group of genetic disorders that affect the development of the vertebrae. This particular subtype is characterized by short stature and multiple skeletal abnormalities, including lordosis, scoliosis, flattened vertebrae, pectus carinatum, coxa vara, clubfoot, and abnormal epiphyses or metaphyses. It has a material basis in mutations in the COL2A1 gene, which is responsible for producing type II collagen, a key component of cartilage and connective tissue. This subtype can be inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that if one parent has the condition, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit it.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 16 (SCAR16) is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by truncal and limb ataxia, resulting in gait instability. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the STUB1 gene on chromosome 16p13. This condition is also known as SCAR16.

Spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia Missouri type, also known as SEMDM, is a genetic disorder that affects the development of the spine and limbs. It is caused by mutations in the MMP13 gene, which results in abnormal metaphyseal changes and genu varum deformities, leading to the characteristic pear-shaped vertebrae seen in this type of dysplasia. The condition primarily affects the spine, but can also impact the limbs. It is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that only one copy of the gene is needed for the disorder to develop.

Fibrous dysplasia is a type of bone remodeling disease that affects the growth and development of bones. It occurs when there is an imbalance in the activity of certain cells in the bone, leading to the replacement of normal bone with fibrous tissue. This can cause the affected bones to become deformed or misshapen, and it may also lead to weakness in the affected area. Fibrous dysplasia most commonly affects the long bones of the arms and legs, but it can also occur in other bones throughout the body. It is usually diagnosed in childhood or adolescence, and it can be treated with medications that inhibit the activity of the cells responsible for the disease.

Craniodiaphyseal dysplasia is a type of osteosclerosis, which refers to the excessive growth of bone tissue. It leads to an increase in calcium concentration within the skull, causing a reduction in the size of cranial foramina and cervical spinal canal. This condition has been assigned MESH code C562940.

craniometaphyseal dysplasia is a type of osteosclerosis that has the specific symptom of increased bone mineral density in the craniofacial bones. This condition can be characterized by hyperostosis and sclerosis of the craniofacial bones, along with abnormal modeling of the metaphyses. It is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of the skull and facial bones, which can lead to abnormal growth, deformities, and other health problems.

sost related sclerosing bone dysplasia, also known as van Buchem disease, is a type of autosomal recessive disorder characterized by the overgrowth of endosteal bone, resulting in dense and wide bones throughout the body, particularly in the skull. It is caused by mutations in the SOST gene.

Worth Syndrome is a genetic disorder characterized by an increase in bone mineral density and the formation of bony structures in the palate. It is caused by a mutation in the LRP5 gene, which results in increased bone density and bony structures located in the palate. Worth Syndrome can also be referred to as autosomal dominant endosteal hyperostosis or autosomal dominant osteosclerosis. It is important to note that Worth Syndrome has a benign form, known as Worth hyperostosis corticalis generalisata with torus platinus.

Pycnodysostosis is a type of autosomal recessive disorder that affects the development and growth of bones. It results from mutations in the CTSK gene, which encodes for a protein involved in chondrocyte differentiation. Individuals with pycnodysostosis typically have short stature, brittle bones, osteopetrosis, and shortening of the distal phalanges.

Axial osteomalacia, also known as primary osteoporosis, is a type of osteosclerosis that occurs in the axial skeleton (the bones of the spine and skull). It is characterized by increased bone mineral density and the formation of thickened bone tissue. This condition can lead to coarsening of the trabecular bone, causing it to become more rigid and less flexible. It is important for individuals with axial osteomalacia to work with their healthcare providers to manage their condition effectively through diet, exercise, and medications, if necessary.

Fibrogenesis imperfecta ossium is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of bone. It is characterized by abnormalities in collagen synthesis, which leads to the formation of lamellar bones. These bones are typically smaller and weaker than normal bones, making them more prone to breaking or fracturing.
The exact cause of Fibrogenesis imperfecta ossium is unknown, but it is believed to be a result of mutations in the genes responsible for collagen production. It can affect people of all ages, but it is most commonly diagnosed in childhood.
There is no cure for Fibrogenesis imperfecta ossium, but treatment options may include medications to reduce pain and improve bone strength, as well as physical therapy and assistive devices to help with mobility. It is important for individuals with this condition to work closely with their healthcare provider to develop a comprehensive treatment plan that meets their unique needs.

Hypochondroplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia, which is a group of genetic disorders that affect the development of bones and cartilage. It is caused by mutations in the FGFR3 gene, which is located on the short arm of chromosome 4. The condition results in short limbs and other skeletal abnormalities, and it is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 18 (SCAR18) is a genetic disorder that affects the cerebellum, a part of the brain responsible for coordination and balance. It is characterized by delayed psychomotor development, severe gait disturbances due to cerebellar ataxia, ocular movement abnormalities, and intellectual disability. The condition is caused by mutations in the GRID2 gene on chromosome 4q22.

Achondrogenesis is a type of osteochondrodysplasia that affects the development of bone and cartilage, leading to short stature, a narrow chest, and other skeletal abnormalities. It has a material basis in deficient endochondral ossification, which results in dwarfism, short-trunk, short-limbed, anascara, disproportionately large cranium, and a narrow chest. If left untreated, it can lead to death in utero or during the early neonatal period.

Hypochondrogenesis is a type of monogenic disease that affects bone growth and results in a small body, hydrops fetalis, and abnormal ossification located in the vertebral column or pelvis. The disease has symptoms such as an enlarged abdomen. It is caused by mutations in the COL2A1 gene which affects the union of the vertebral column and bony pelvis.

Kniest dysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia that has material basis in mutations in the COL2A1 gene, which results in dwarfism with short trunk and limbs, as well as vision and hearing problems. The disease also has symptoms such as large joints, wide set eyes, and a round flat face. It is an autosomal dominant disease that at least has phenotype some malar flattening and severe short stature.

Stickler syndrome, also known as arthro-osteo-mucopolysaccharidosis (AOMPS) or mucolipidosis type IV, is a rare genetic disorder. It affects many body systems including the eyes, ears, joints, and bones. The exact cause of Stickler syndrome is not known but it is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner. Symptoms can include distinctive facial features such as a thin nose, large ears, high palate, and protruding eyes. Additionally, individuals with Stickler syndrome may experience hearing loss, joint problems, and other health issues.

Pseudoachondroplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia, which is a genetic disorder that affects the development of bones and joints. It is characterized by short limbs and dwarfism, and is caused by mutations in the COMP gene. The condition has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, meaning that it can be passed down through family genes. Some other synonyms for pseudoachondroplasia include spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia and pseudoachondroplastic dysplasia.

Acromesomelic dysplasia is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of bones and cartilage in the body, primarily involving the limbs. It results in short stature due to both mesomelia (shortening of the long bones) and acromelia (underdevelopment or absence of certain bones). The condition is usually diagnosed during childhood and can cause various physical and developmental issues. Treatment options may include surgery, medications, and physical therapy to manage symptoms and improve quality of life.

Acromesomelic dysplasia Maroteaux type is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of bones and cartilage in the spine, resulting in abnormal curvature of the spine (scoliosis) and short stature. It is caused by mutations in the NPR2 gene, which encodes a protein involved in cholesterol metabolism. The disorder also affects the limbs, causing abnormalities such as bowing and shortening of the bones. The exact synonym for this disorder is acromesomelic dysplasia-1.

Acromesomelic dysplasia Hunter Thompson type is a type of acromesomelic dysplasia, which is an abnormal development of bones in the arms and legs. It's caused by mutations in the AMDH gene, resulting in normal growth of the axial skeleton (the central part of the body) but fusion of the bones located in the hands or feet. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. The exact synonyms for this type of acromesomelic dysplasia are acromesomelic dwarfism and acromesomelic dysplasia-2C.

acromesomelic dysplasia grebe type is a condition that affects the development of bones and joints. It is caused by a mutation in the CDMP-1 gene, which results in the absence of certain bones and finger and toe deformities. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Albright's hereditary osteodystrophy is a type of pseudohypoparathyroidism, characterized by short stature, obesity, and a rounded face. It results from a lack of responsiveness to parathyroid hormone, which leads to shortening and widening of the long bones in the hands or feet. It is also sometimes referred to as pseudohypoparathyroidism type 1a.

Achondrogenesis type Ia, also known as the Houston-Harris type, is a form of autosomal recessive disorder that affects the development of bones in the spine. It results from abnormal ossification of the vertebral column or spine, leading to short stature and other skeletal abnormalities. The disease has a location on the vertebral column, which is affected by the genetic inheritance pattern.

Achondrogenesis type I, also known as achondroplasia or the most common form of short-limbed dwarfism, is a genetic disorder that occurs due to an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern. It affects the development of cartilage and bone in the body, resulting in short stature and characteristic physical features such as a large head, prominent eyes, and normal to low-normal IQ. The condition is caused by mutations in the fibroblast growth factor receptor 3 (FGFR3) gene on chromosome 4. There are two types of achondrogenesis: type I and type II. Type I affects the development of the arms, legs, spine, and overall body structure, while type II primarily affects the arms and spine. Both types can cause health problems related to the spinal column and other organs, but the severity varies among affected individuals. Achondrogenesis type II is less common than achondrogenesis type I and has a milder phenotype.

Achondrogenesis type II is a genetic disorder characterized by underdeveloped lungs, hydrops fetalis, and abnormal ossification of the vertebral column or pelvis. It is caused by mutations in the COL2A1 gene, which leads to weakened collagen production in these areas. This condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that a single copy of the mutated gene is enough to cause the disorder.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 15 (SCAR15) is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by the homozygous mutation in the RUBCN gene on chromosome 3q29. It has the same clinical features as spinocerebellar ataxia 15, including atypical gait, pyramidal signs, and cerebellar atrophy. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 14 (SCAR14) is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by delayed psychomotor development, severe early-onset gait ataxia, eye movement abnormalities, cerebellar atrophy on brain imaging, and intellectual disability due to homozygous mutation in the SPTBN2 gene on chromosome 11q13.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 7, also known as SCAR7, is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia. It is characterized by the onset of progressive gait difficulties, eye movement abnormalities, and dysarthria in the first or second decade of life. It is caused by compound heterozygous mutations in the TPP1 gene on chromosome 11p15.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 12 (SCAR12) is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by onset of generalized seizures in infancy, delayed psychomotor development with mental retardation, and cerebellar ataxia. It has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the WWOX gene on chromosome 16q23.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 2 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia that is characterized by juvenile onset of progressive cerebellar ataxia, axonal sensorimotor peripheral neuropathy, and increased serum alpha-fetoprotein. It has a genetic basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the senataxin gene on chromosome 9q34. It is also known as SCAR2.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 13 (SCAR13) is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by delayed psychomotor development beginning in infancy and caused by homozygous mutation in the GRM1 gene on chromosome 6q24.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia type 11 (ARSCA11) is a genetic disorder that affects the cerebellum, which is responsible for coordination and balance. It is caused by mutations in the SYT14 gene on chromosome 1q32. ARSCA11 is an autosomal recessive disorder, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the defective gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. Symptoms typically begin in childhood and can include poor balance and coordination, muscle stiffness, and difficulty with fine motor skills. There is no cure for ARSCA11, but treatments can help manage symptoms.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 17 (SCAR17) is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by progressive loss of coordination and balance (ataxia). It is caused by mutations in the CWF19L1 gene, which is located on chromosome 10q24.

autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 19 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia. Autosomal recessive means that both copies of the gene need to be mutated for the condition to be expressed, and recessive means that it only expresses when both copies are present. Spinocerebellar ataxia refers to a group of disorders affecting the cerebellum and spinal cord. Ataxia is a lack of coordination and balance. Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 19 specifically has postnatal onset, which means it starts after birth, and progresses rapidly. It is characterized by severe progressive sensorineural hearing loss and progressive cerebellar ataxia, both of which are caused by a mutation in the SLC9A1 gene located on chromosome 1p36. The condition has also been referred to as Lichtenstein-Knorr syndrome and SCAR19.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 20 (SCAR20) is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia. It is characterized by severely delayed psychomotor development with poor or absent speech, wide-based or absent gait, coarse facies, and cerebellar atrophy. The condition has a genetic basis, specifically homozygous mutation in the SNX14 gene on chromosome 6q14.<|end|>

Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type 5, also known as hereditary motor and sensory neuropathy with pyramidal features, is a type of Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease that is characterized by pyramidal features including extensor plantar responses, mild increase in tone, and preserved or increased reflexes but no spastic gait. It is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which means it has material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.

CMT type 6, also known as Hereditary Motor and Sensory Neuropathy Type VI, is a subtype of Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease characterized by early-onset optic atrophy leading to progressive visual loss, along with peripheral axonal sensorimotor neuropathy. The age of onset and severity can vary greatly among individuals affected by this condition.

type 7 Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease is a form of the condition that affects the peripheral nerves. It is characterized by optic atrophy, which means the gradual loss of vision, and retinitis pigmentosa, which causes the breakdown of the retina.

Mucolipidosis II, also known as I-cell disease or inclusion-cell disease, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by short stature, skeletal abnormalities, cardiomegaly (enlarged heart), and developmental delay. It is caused by mutations in the GNPTAB gene, which encodes an enzyme involved in the proper functioning of lysosomes, resulting in the accumulation of lysosomal substrates within cells. This leads to the formation of inclusion bodies, which can damage various organs and tissues in the body. Mucolipidosis II is typically diagnosed in early childhood and can have a severe impact on an individual's overall health and quality of life. Treatment options are limited, and management often focuses on supporting the affected child's growth and development, as well as addressing any complications that may arise.

mucolipidosis III is a type of autosomal recessive disease where there's mutation in the gene encoding the alpha/beta-subunits precursor gene of GLcNAc-phosphotransferase. This leads to a deficiency in the enzyme that converts glycolipids to glycosphingolipids, resulting in the accumulation of glycosphingolipid in lysosomes.

Intestinal pseudo obstruction (IP) is a type of colonic disease characterized by bowel obstruction resulting from impairment of the muscle contractions that move food through the digestive tract. Another name for this condition is neuronal intestinal dysplasia, which refers to abnormal neural development in the enteric nervous system. The enteric nervous system (ENS) is a complex network of neurons located in the walls of the gastrointestinal tract that control its movements and functions. Impairment or dysfunction of this system can lead to IP, which may be caused by various factors such as inflammation, injury, or genetic defects. In some cases, IP may be treated with surgery or other interventions, while in others it may require lifelong management with medications and dietary changes.

Spina bifida occulta is a type of spina bifida that occurs when there are minor splits in the vertebrae, but the outer part of some of the vertebrae is still closed. It is characterized by a small protrusion or dimple on the back, and usually does not cause any major problems. However, it can still affect a person's mobility and may require treatment such as surgery or physical therapy.

Neural tube defects are a type of congenital disorder that occurs when the neural tube, which is the precursor to the brain and spinal cord, fails to close properly during embryonic development. This can lead to a variety of abnormalities in the development of the central nervous system, including anencephaly (the absence of most of the brain and skull), meningomyelocele (exposure of the brain and spinal cord through an opening in the skull), and spina bifida (a type of myelomeningocele). Neural tube defects can be prevented with proper folic acid supplementation during pregnancy.

Neu-Laxova syndrome type 2 is a rare genetic disorder caused by a deficiency of the amino acid serine. It is characterized by multiple severe symptoms, including ichthyosis (a skin condition), microcephaly (a small head size), central nervous system abnormalities, limb deformities, intrauterine growth restriction, proptosis (a condition causing eyeballs to bulge forward), anasarca (edema caused by excess fluid trapped in body cavities), and micrognathia (a small jaw). The disorder is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a child must inherit two copies of the mutated gene from their parents to develop the condition.

Neu-Laxova syndrome, also known as serine deficiency syndrome or PHGDH deficiency, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by multiple severe birth defects. These defects include ichthyosis (a skin condition), microcephaly (small head size), central nervous system abnormalities, limb deformities, intrauterine growth restriction, proptosis (elevation of the eyeball), anasarca (edema caused by excess fluid in the body), and micrognathia (underdeveloped jaw). It is caused by a mutation in the PHGDH gene located on chromosome 1p12.

Hypophosphatemic nephrolithiasis osteoporosis 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by low levels of phosphorus in the blood, leading to the formation of kidney stones and weak bones. This condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the SLC34A1 gene on chromosome 5q35.

Hypophosphatemic nephrolithiasis osteoporosis 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by low levels of phosphorus in the blood and urine, leading to the formation of kidney stones and bone loss. It is caused by mutations in the SLC9A3R1 gene on chromosome 17q25.1.

Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which means that it has been inherited from one or more affected individuals in the family line. It is characterized by excessive longitudinal striations and numerous superficial pits on the nails, giving them a distinctive rough, sand paper-like appearance.
Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 1 has been described as having an abnormality of prenatal development or birth as its basis, which means that it occurs due to a problem with how the affected individual's body developed before they were born. It is also sometimes referred to as twenty-nail dystrophy.
nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which means that one copy of the gene for this condition is enough to increase the risk of developing the disease. It can also be inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that an individual must inherit two copies of the gene, one from each parent, to develop the disorder. Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 3 is characterized by white discoloration of the nails and has a material basis in some abnormalities of prenatal development or birth.

Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 4, also known as anonychia congenita, is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by the complete absence or severe hypoplasia of all fingernails and toenails without significant bone anomalies, and has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the R-spondin-4 gene on chromosome 20p13.

Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 5 (also known as "nail dystrophy") is a genetic condition that can be passed down through generations in families. It is characterized by abnormal nail growth, including thick and hard nails, and a straight or concave proximal edge of detachment. The exact cause of this disorder is unknown, but it may be due to an abnormality during fetal development. Treatment options for nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 5 typically focus on managing the symptoms and improving the appearance of the affected nails.

nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 6 refers to a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by partial absences of the fingernails or toenails. This condition can also be referred to as simply "nail dysplasia." It is important to note that this condition has a genetic component, and can be passed down through families. However, it is not associated with any specific syndrome or pattern of physical abnormalities.

Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 7, also known as Nail pigmentation abnormalities, is a condition that affects the appearance of the fingernails and toenails. It is characterized by nails with longitudinal streaks, thinning of the nail plate, poorly developed or absent lunulae, and variously disturbed formation of the nail plate leading to increased vulnerability of the free nail margins. Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder 7 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which means it can be inherited from one parent and passed down through families.

Tubular aggregate myopathy 1, also known as TAM1, is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the muscles. It has a narrow match ORDO of 2593 and is characterized by the presence of tubular aggregates in myofibrils. The exact cause of this condition is unknown but it has been linked to mutations in the STIM1 gene on chromosome 11p15.

Reduced body myopathy 1a, also known as FSHD, is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles in the body. It is caused by a defect in the DNA of the X chromosome and can lead to muscle weakness, especially in the arms, legs, and shoulders. There is currently no cure for this condition, but there are treatments available to help manage its symptoms.
myofibrillar myopathy 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

Myofibrillar myopathy 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by the presence of abnormal proteins in muscle tissue. It is caused by mutations in the alpha-B-crystallin gene on chromosome 11q23, which leads to a deficiency in this protein. This can result in weakness and degeneration of muscle fibers, leading to various symptoms such as muscle stiffness, weakness, and difficulty with movement. The condition is often inherited from one's parents, but there are cases where it may develop spontaneously due to new mutations or genetic changes.

Myofibrillar myopathy 3, also known as LGMD1A or autosomal dominant limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 1A, is a genetic disorder characterized by progressive muscle weakness and wasting. It primarily affects the skeletal muscles responsible for movement and can lead to significant disability if left untreated. The condition is caused by mutations in the MYOT gene on chromosome 5q31, which encodes a protein called myotilin. Myofibrillar myopathy 3 has an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern, meaning that a person with one copy of the gene can pass it on to their children. There is no cure for the condition, but physical therapy and other treatments may help slow its progression and improve quality of life.

Myofibrillar myopathy 4 (Miyoshi muscular dystrophy) is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles. It is an autosomal dominant disease, which means that if one parent has the gene, there is a 50% chance that their child will inherit it. The condition is caused by mutations in the ZASP gene on chromosome 10.
Myofibrillar myopathy 4 (Miyoshi muscular dystrophy) is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles. It is a type of myofibrillar myopathy, which refers to a group of inherited muscle diseases characterized by the gradual weakening and wasting of muscle tissue.
Myofibrillar myopathy 4 (Miyoshi muscular dystrophy) is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles. It has an exact synonym, zaspopathy, which is also a type of myofibrillar myopathy.

Myofibrillar myopathy 5 (MFMI5) is a subtype of Myofibrillar myopathies, which are characterized by the selective weakness of skeletal muscle fibers. MFMI5 is an autosomal dominant disorder caused by mutations in the FLNC gene on chromosome 7q32. The term "filaminopathy" is also used to describe this condition, as the protein filamin A is involved in the pathogenesis of the disease. It is important to note that myofibrillar myopathies are distinct from other types of muscular dystrophy, and have a different clinical course and treatment approach.
Myofibrillar myopathy 6 is a type of muscle disease that results from the BAG3 gene on chromosome 10q26 being mutated in an autosomal dominant manner.

Myofibrillar myopathy 7 (MFM7) is a type of autosomal recessive disease, characterized by the progressive skeletal muscle weakness and degeneration. It is caused by mutations in the KY gene located on chromosome 3q22. The condition affects both children and adults but is more severe in childhood. Symptoms include muscle pain, weakness, and stiffness, as well as limited mobility and difficulty in performing daily activities. There is no cure for MFM7, but treatment options may include physical therapy, medications, and assistive devices to manage symptoms.

Myopathy, lactic acidosis, and sideroblastic anemia (MLASA) is a rare type of mitochondrial disease. It is characterized by progressive exercise intolerance that starts in childhood, onset of sideroblastic anemia around adolescence, lactic acidosis, and myopathy.

Compton North Congenital Myopathy is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects muscle strength and development. It is characterized by severe neonatal hypotonia, severe generalized skeletal, bulbar and respiratory muscle weakness, multiple flexion contractures, and normal creatine kinase serum levels. The condition has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the CNTN1 gene on chromosome 12q12 and can be diagnosed through prenatal testing and physical examination.

Congenital myopathy 4a, also known as CFTD (congenital fiber-type disproportion), is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects skeletal muscle. It is characterized by weakness in the muscles of the shoulders, upper arms, hips, and thighs. The exact cause of this condition is not yet fully understood, but it is believed to be related to abnormalities in the development or growth of muscle fibers. There is no cure for congenital myopathy 4a, but treatment options may include physical therapy, medications to manage symptoms, and assistive devices such as wheelchairs or walkers. With proper care and management, people with this condition can lead a fulfilling life.
cylindrical spirals myopathy is a type of congenital myopathy characterized by global muscle weakness, hypotonia, and cramps in the presence of cylindrical, spiral-shaped inclusions.

Microcephaly and chorioretinopathy 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by delayed psychomotor development and visual impairment, often accompanied by short stature, and has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TUBGCP6 gene.

Microcephaly and chorioretinopathy 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that can be caused by homozygous mutation in the PLK4 gene. It is characterized by delayed psychomotor development, visual impairment, and short stature.

Microcephaly and chorioretinopathy 3 is a rare genetic disorder characterized by congenital microcephaly (small head) and chorioretinal dysplasia (abnormal development of the retina), which can lead to poor vision and nystagmus. It has a strong genetic component, with mutations in the TUBGCP4 gene being the most common cause. The severity of the condition varies among affected individuals, but it generally results in significant physical and cognitive disabilities.
Myoglobinuria is a type of myopathy characterized by an increased urinary excretion of myoglobin.

Infantile myofibromatosis (IM) is a benign tumor that grows in connective tissue, which includes the skin, muscles, and bones. It is most commonly found in children and young adults, and can cause pain, swelling, and limited mobility if it affects muscles or joints. While it can occur in any part of the body, it often grows on the trunk, arms, legs, head, neck, spine, and skull. It is also possible for IM to spread to other organs in rare cases. The exact cause of IM is not known, but it may be related to genetic or environmental factors. Treatment options include surgery, radiation therapy, and chemotherapy.
Contractures, pterygia and spondylocarpotarsal fusion syndrome is a type of monogenic disease.

Mitochondrial complex III deficiency, nuclear type 1 is a rare and severe mitochondrial disorder caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the BCS1L gene on chromosome 2q35. It presents with lactic acidosis, hypotonia, hypoglycemia, failure to thrive, encephalopathy, and delayed psychomotor development at birth. The condition has a material basis in the structural variant of the BCS1L gene, which encodes for a protein important for mitochondrial complex III function.

Mitochondrial complex III deficiency, nuclear type 3 refers to a specific type of mitochondrial complex III deficiency where the underlying cause is due to homozygous mutation in the UQCRB gene located on chromosome 8q22.

Mitochondrial complex III deficiency, also known as mitochondrial cytochrome c oxidase III deficiency, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the function of the mitochondria, which are responsible for producing energy in cells. It is caused by mutations in one of several genes that encode proteins involved in complex III, including UQCRQ.

Mitochondrial complex III deficiency can present with a variety of symptoms depending on the severity and the specific gene affected. Symptoms may include fatigue, weakness, exercise intolerance, and muscle pain or cramps. In some cases, it can also cause lactic acidosis, which is an excess build-up of lactic acid in the blood.

There is no cure for mitochondrial complex III deficiency, but treatment options may include dietary modifications, medications to reduce muscle symptoms, and supportive care to manage complications. It is important for individuals with this disorder to work closely with their healthcare providers to develop an individualized treatment plan that addresses their specific needs and symptoms.

Mitochondrial complex III deficiency, nuclear type 5 is a specific subtype of Mitochondrial Complex III Deficiency. It is characterized by neonatal onset of severe metabolic acidosis associated with hyperammonemia and hypoglycemia. The underlying cause of this condition is homozygous mutation in the UQCRC2 gene on chromosome 16p12.

Mitochondrial complex III deficiency, nuclear type 6 is a specific type of Mitochondrial Complex III Deficiency. It's characterized by the onset of episodic acute lactic acidosis, ketoacidosis, and insulin-responsive hyperglycemia in early childhood, often accompanied by infections. This condition is caused by homozygous mutation in the CYC1 gene located on chromosome 8q24.

Mitochondrial complex III deficiency, also known as the CIII complex or the Coenzyme QH2-oxidoreductase complex, is a part of the electron transport chain within mitochondria. This complex plays an essential role in generating ATP through the oxidative phosphorylation process. Mitochondrial complex III deficiency can result from mutations in specific genes, such as UQCC2, which is located on chromosome 6p21.
Mitochondrial complex III deficiency has two main types: nuclear and mitochondrial. Nuclear-type 7 (mitochondrial complex III deficiency nuclear type 7) specifically refers to a subtype of the nuclear-type, which is characterized by a homozygous mutation in the UQCC2 gene on chromosome 6p21. This particular form of the deficiency has a basis in structural variations and can lead to various health issues if left untreated.
It's important to note that mitochondrial complex III deficiency is a rare condition, but it can have severe consequences on an individual's overall health. Therefore, it is crucial to seek professional medical advice for proper diagnosis and management of this condition.

Mitochondrial complex III deficiency, nuclear type 8, is a specific form of mitochondrial complex III deficiency that has a genetic basis. It is caused by homozygous mutations in the LYRM7 gene on chromosome 5q23. This condition leads to childhood-onset progressive neurodegeneration.

Mitochondrial complex III deficiency, also known as succinate dehydrogenase (SDH) deficiency, is a rare genetic disorder caused by mutations in the SDH gene. This condition affects the mitochondria, which are small structures within cells that produce energy. When these structures are affected, it can lead to a lack of energy production and result in various symptoms, such as fatigue, weakness, exercise intolerance, and muscle cramps. Additionally, there is an increased risk of developing cancer due to the accumulation of damaged mitochondria over time. Mitochondrial complex III deficiency can occur in both children and adults, but it is more common in people with Finnish or Ashkenazi Jewish ancestry. Treatment usually involves dietary adjustments, medications, and exercise therapy to manage symptoms, although there is no cure for the condition at this time.

Mitochondrial DNA Depletion Syndrome 1, also known as MNGIE type or TYMP-related mitochondrial neurogastrointestinal encephalopathy syndrome, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the function of mitochondria in the body. It is characterized by onset between the second and fifth decades of life with symptoms such as ptosis (drooping eyelids), progressive external ophthalmoplegia (loss of muscle control in the eyes), gastrointestinal dysmotility, cachexia (wasting away of body tissue), diffuse leukoencephalopathy (decreased brain function), peripheral neuropathy, and mitochondrial dysfunction. The disorder is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the nuclear-encoded thymidine phosphorylase gene on chromosome 22q13. It is an autosomal recessive inheritance disorder, which means that to develop the disease, a person must inherit two copies of the faulty gene, one from each parent.

Mitochondrial DNA Depletion Syndrome 2, also known as TK2-related mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome or the myopathic form, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects muscle function. It is characterized by childhood onset of muscle weakness and is caused by a mutation in the mitochondrial thymidine kinase gene on chromosome 16q21.

mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 3, also known as deoxyguanosine kinase deficiency, is a rare genetic disorder that affects infants. It is characterized by progressive liver failure, neurologic abnormalities, hypoglycemia, and increased lactate levels in body fluids. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the deoxyguanosine kinase gene located on chromosome 2p13.

Alpers Huttenlocher Syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by psychomotor retardation, intractable epilepsy, and liver failure in infants and young children. The syndrome has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the nuclear gene encoding mitochondrial DNA polymerase gamma on chromosome 15q26. It is also known by several other names, including Alper's syndrome and Diffuse Cerebral Sclerosis of Schilder.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 4b, also known as Mitochondrial Neurogastrointestinal Encephalopathy Syndrome (MNGIE), is a genetic disorder that affects the mitochondria, which are responsible for providing energy to cells. It is caused by a mutation in the mitochondrial DNA polymerase gamma gene on chromosome 15q26, and it typically presents with symptoms such as muscle weakness, chronic gastrointestinal dysmotility, cachexia, progressive external ophthalmoplegia, axonal sensory ataxic neuropathy, and pseudoobstruction. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, meaning that it is passed down through families in a pattern where the affected individual has a 25% chance of passing on the disorder to each of their offspring.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 5, also known as succinate-CoA ligase deficiency, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects infants. It is characterized by infantile onset of hypotonia, progressive neurologic deterioration, a hyperkinetic-dystonic movement disorder, external ophthalmoplegia, deafness, and variable renal tubular dysfunction. The disease has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the beta subunit of the succinate-CoA ligase gene on chromosome 13q14.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 6, also known as MPV17-related hepatocerebral mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome and Navajo neurohepatopathy, is a rare genetic disorder that primarily affects the liver and the brain. It is characterized by infantile onset of progressive liver failure, often leading to death in the first year of life, and has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the mitochondrial inner membrane protein MPV17 gene on chromosome 2p23. This disorder is caused by a deficiency in mitochondrial DNA, which leads to dysfunction and failure of the mitochondria, ultimately affecting energy production and cellular metabolism in the body. There is no cure for this condition, but early diagnosis and supportive care can improve quality of life for those affected.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 7, also known as Oha-Ho Syndrome or infantile onset spinocerebellar ataxia, is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by progressive ataxia, hypotonia, hyporeflexia, athetosis, and sensory impairment. It is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the C10ORF2 gene, which encodes for the twinkle and twinky proteins located on chromosome 10q24.

Mitochondrial DNA Depletion Syndrome 8a is a rare genetic disorder that affects the mitochondria in the body, which are responsible for producing energy. It is an autosomal recessive disease, meaning it is passed down through generations by both parents and requires two copies of the mutated gene to develop the condition. The symptoms include neonatal hypotonia, lactic acidosis, and neurologic deterioration.
