It is also known as RRM2B-related mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome, encephalomyopathic form with renal tubulopathy.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 9 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects infants and is characterized by symptoms such as hypotonia, lactic acidosis, severe psychomotor retardation, progressive neurologic deterioration, and excretion of methylmalonic acid. It has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the alpha subunit of the succinate-CoA ligase gene on chromosome 2p11. Another name for this condition is fatal infantile lactic acidosis.

Mitochondrial DNA Depletion Syndrome 11 (also known as PEO-myopathy-emaciation syndrome) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the mitochondria, which are responsible for producing energy in cells. It presents with symptoms such as progressive external ophthalmoplegia (PEO), muscle weakness and atrophy, exercise intolerance, and respiratory insufficiency due to muscle weakness. The disease has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, which means that it is passed down through generations of a family when both parents pass on the same gene.

Mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 12a is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by severe hypotonia due to mitochondrial dysfunction apparent at birth and has a material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of heterozygous mutation in the solute carrier family 25 member 4 gene on chromosome 4q35.

Mitochondrial DNA Depletion Syndrome 13 (FBXL4-related encephalomyopathic mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome) is a rare genetic disorder that affects infants and young children. It is caused by mutations in the F-box and leucine rich repeat protein 4 gene (FBXL4) located on chromosome 6q16. The condition leads to an early onset of encephalopathy, hypotonia, lactic acidosis, and severe global developmental delay. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that to have the disorder, a child must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent. There is no cure for the condition, but treatments can help manage its symptoms.

Sengers syndrome, also known as mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome 10 (cardiomyopathic type), is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple organ systems, including the heart, muscles, and eyes. It is characterized by congenital cataracts, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, skeletal myopathy, exercise intolerance, and lactic acidosis. However, affected individuals typically have normal mental development. The disorder is caused by a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the acylglycerol kinase gene (AGK) located on chromosome 7q34. It is an autosomal recessive inheritance disease.

Multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome 1, also known as NFU1 deficiency, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by weakness, respiratory failure, lack of neurologic development, lactic acidosis, and early death. It is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the NFU1 iron-sulfur cluster scaffold gene on chromosome 2p13.

Multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome 2, also known as BOLA3 deficiency, is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by increased serum glycine and lactate, developmental regression in infancy, an encephalopathic disease course with seizures, spasticity, loss of head control, and abnormal movement. It has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the bolA family member 3 gene on chromosome 2p13.

Multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome 3, also known as IBA57 deficiency, is a rare autosomal recessive disorder characterized by the loss of previously acquired developmental milestones in the first months or years of life. It is caused by homozygous mutation in the iron-sulfur cluster assembly factor IBA57 gene on chromosome 1q42.

Multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome 4 (MMDS4) is a type of autosomal recessive disorder that affects the functioning of mitochondria in the body. Mitochondria are responsible for producing energy and are crucial for various cellular processes. In MMDS4, there is a combination of multiple dysfunctions in these mitochondria, leading to a range of symptoms and health problems.

One of the main features of MMDS4 is that it presents with normal development during the first months of life, followed by a gradual decline in motor skills and muscle tone, spasticity, and nystagmus (involuntary eye movements). This progression usually leads to death in early childhood.

The genetic basis of MMDS4 is related to autosomal recessive inheritance. It is caused by mutations in the IRONS2 gene located on chromosome 14q24. Homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in this gene can lead to the development of MMDS4.

In summary, Multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome 4 is a severe and life-threatening disorder that affects multiple organ systems and leads to progressive loss of motor and social skills. It has a genetic basis related to autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically mutations in the IRONS2 gene on chromosome 14q24.

Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia Type 4 (MEN4) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by hyperparathyroidism and multiple endocrine tumors. It has a material basis in mutations in the CDKN1B gene on chromosome 12p13, which results in a reduction in the amount of functional p27 tumor suppressor protein. This allows cells to grow and divide unchecked, leading to the development of the disease. MEN4 is also known as Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia, Type IV (MENIV).

Multiple Congenital Anomalies, Hypotonia and Seizures Syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease. Multiple Congenital Anomalies, Hypotonia and Seizures Syndrome 1 is a type of Multiple Congenital Anomalies, Hypotonia and Seizures Syndrome. Multiple Congenital Anomalies, Hypotonia and Seizures Syndrome 1 is a type of something that at least has material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Multiple Congenital Anomalies, Hypotonia and Seizures Syndrome 1 is a type of something that at least disease has basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. Multiple Congenital Anomalies, Hypotonia and Seizures Syndrome 1 has definition A multiple congenital anomalies-hypotonia-seizures syndrome characterized by neonatal hypotonia, lack of psychomotor development, seizures, dysmorphic features, and variable congenital anomalies involving the cardiac, urinary, and gastrointestinal systems and has_material_basis_in homozygous mutation in the PIGN gene on chromosome 18q21.

Multiple Congenital Anomalies-Hypotonia-Seizures Syndrome 2, also known as Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 20 or Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 20, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by X-linked recessive inheritance of dysmorphic features, neonatal hypotonia, myoclonic seizures and variable abnormalities involving the central nervous, cardiac, and urinary systems. It has been found that mutations in the PIGA gene on chromosome Xp22 are the causative factor for this syndrome.

Multiple Congenital Anomalies Hypotonia Seizures Syndrome 3 is a rare genetic disorder that affects various bodily functions. It is characterized by multiple congenital anomalies, hypotonia (weakness), and seizures. The syndrome has a strong genetic component, with mutations in the PIGT gene on chromosome 20q13 being the primary cause. The disorder can also affect the cardiac, urinary, and gastrointestinal systems, as well as cause dysmorphic features such as abnormal facial development. It is sometimes referred to by its synonyms: M syndrome or light fixation seizure syndrome.

Mosaic Variegated Aneuploidy Syndrome 1 (MVAS1) is a rare genetic disorder that affects an individual's growth and development. It is characterized by slow growth before and after birth, short stature, an unusually small head size, and an increased risk of developing cancer in childhood. MVAS1 has a autosomal recessive inheritance pattern, which means that to develop the disease, an individual must inherit two copies of the faulty gene, one from each parent. The gene responsible for MVAS1 is BUB1B, located on chromosome 15q15.

Mosaic Variegated Aneuploidy Syndrome 2 (MVAS2) is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of certain parts of the body. It is characterized by mosaicism, which means that some cells in the body have an abnormal number of chromosomes. MVAS2 has a specific pattern of chromosome abnormalities and can cause various physical and cognitive problems. The exact cause of this disorder is not known, but it is thought to be inherited in an autosomal recessive manner. This means that a person must inherit two copies of the faulty gene (one from each parent) in order to develop the condition. MVAS2 typically begins before and after birth, with symptoms including intellectual disability, seizures, feeding difficulties, and other developmental delays. The severity of the condition can vary widely depending on the specific chromosome abnormalities present and the individual's overall health. There is no cure for MVAS2, but early intervention and proper medical care can help manage the symptoms and improve quality of life.

Congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles is a type of ocular motility disease, characterized by the inability to move the eyes in certain directions and droopy eyelids. It has a basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth, leading to the congenital malformation of the extraocular muscles.

Childhood Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia is a type of leukemia that affects children. It is an acute form of the disease, which means it progresses quickly and can be life-threatening if not treated promptly. The cancer cells in this type of leukemia are immature lymphocytes, which are a type of white blood cell. These cells multiply rapidly and can crowd out healthy blood cells, leading to anemia, infections, and other complications. Treatment for Childhood Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia typically involves chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and stem cell transplantation. The specific treatment plan will depend on the age of the child, the extent of the disease, and other factors.

childhood T cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia is a type of childhood acute lymphocytic leukemia that has a material basis in T cells. It also has the exact synonym T-cell childhood acute lymphoblastic leukemia and childhood precursor T-lymphoblastic lymphoma/leukemia.
childhood B-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia (B-ALL) is a type of childhood cancer that affects the bone marrow and blood. It

Lymphoblastic lymphoma is a type of lymphoma that has a material basis in immature malignant lymphocytes (lymphoblasts) committed to the B-cell or T-cell lineage and is primarily located in lymph nodes or extranodal sites.
t cell childhood lymphoblastic lymphoma is a type of lymphoblastic lymphoma that occurs during childhood and has a material basis in T cells.

Adult acute monocytic leukemia (AAM) is a type of cancer that affects the bone marrow and blood. It is also known as Acute Myeloid Leukemia (AML). AAM occurs when the bone marrow produces an abnormal number of white blood cells called monocytes, which can be harmful to the body. These abnormal monocytes do not mature into healthy blood cells and instead of continuing to grow and divide, they continue to multiply uncontrollably. AAM is considered a rapidly progressive disease that can lead to anemia, infections, and bleeding if left untreated. Treatment options depend on the subtype of AML and patient's age and overall health.

Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) deficiency is a type of hypopituitarism, which refers to the underproduction or absence of one or more pituitary hormones. ACTH deficiency specifically refers to a lack of adrenocorticotropic hormone production by the pituitary gland. This can lead to a condition known as primary adrenal insufficiency, also known as Addison's disease, where the body is unable to produce enough cortisol, a hormone that regulates blood sugar levels and responds to stress. Symptoms of ACTH deficiency may include fatigue, weakness, weight loss, abdominal pain, low blood pressure, nausea, vomiting, and increased thirst. Treatment typically involves replacing the missing hormones with medication.

Medium Chain Acyl-CoA Dehydrogenase Deficiency (MCADD) is a metabolic disorder that occurs due to the deficiency of the enzyme medium chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase. This enzyme plays a crucial role in breaking down medium-chain fatty acids, which are used as an energy source during fasting or periods of low calorie intake. When this enzyme is deficient, it results in the accumulation of these fatty acids and can lead to serious health issues, particularly in infants and young children. Symptoms may include weakness, vomiting, rapid heartbeat, lethargy, seizures, and even coma or death if left untreated. Diagnosis is usually made through newborn screening tests and treatment options may include dietary modifications, medication, and in some cases, liver transplantation.

Short Chain Acyl-CoA Dehydrogenase Deficiency is a lipid metabolism disorder. It is characterized by the enzyme Short Chain Acyl-CoA Dehydrogenase being deficient, leading to the inability to convert short chain fatty acids.

Very long chain acyl-CoA dehydrogenase deficiency (VLCAD) is a genetic disorder that affects the metabolism of fatty acids in the body. It occurs when the body is unable to convert very long chain fatty acids into energy, which can lead to serious health problems if left untreated. Symptoms may include poor growth, vomiting, weakness, and even sudden death, particularly during physical activity or emotional stress. Treatment typically involves a special diet that is low in saturated fat and high in carbohydrates and protein, as well as medication to help the body convert fatty acids into energy.

Congenital adrenal hypoplasia is a condition where the adrenal glands do not develop properly in an individual. This can lead to a lack of hormones that are essential for maintaining proper bodily functions, such as cortisol and aldosterone. It is typically inherited in an X-linked recessive pattern, which means that it is passed down through the mother's side of the family. In some cases, it can also be caused by exposure to certain drugs or environmental factors during fetal development. Congenital adrenal hypoplasia can cause a variety of symptoms, including low blood pressure, abnormal genital development, and excessive hair growth. It is important for people with congenital adrenal hypoplasia to work closely with their healthcare providers to manage their symptoms and ensure proper hormone replacement therapy.

Herpes simplex virus keratitis is a type of keratitis that occurs due to infection by the herpes simplex virus. It is characterized by inflammation and erosion of the cornea, which can lead to pain, redness, and sensitivity to light.
Dendritic keratitis is another name for herpes simplex virus keratitis, which refers to the presence of small, branching dendritic-like structures in the cornea. These structures can cause further inflammation and damage to the cornea, potentially leading to scarring and vision loss if left untreated.
It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have herpes simplex virus keratitis, as prompt treatment with antiviral medications can help prevent the spread of the infection and reduce the risk of long-term complications.

Cryptococcal meningitis is a type of fungal meningitis that occurs when the cryptococcus fungus infects the membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord. It has a material basis in a Crypococcus fungal infection, which causes inflammation of the meninges and can lead to symptoms such as headache, fever, stiff neck, and confusion or other neurological symptoms.

Cytomegalovirus retinitis is a type of retinitis that has a material basis in the Cytomegalovirus. It refers to inflammation or infection of the retina due to this virus, which can lead to vision loss if left untreated. The exact synonym for this condition is CMV retinitis.

Cutaneous candidiasis is a type of skin infection caused by the overgrowth of Candida fungus on the skin. It can cause itching, redness, and sometimes blisters or lesions. The condition is more common in people with weakened immune systems, such as those with HIV/AIDS or cancer undergoing chemotherapy. Treatment typically involves antifungal medication applied to the skin or taken orally.
Lupus nephritis is a type of glomerulonephritis, which is characterized by inflammation of the kidneys resulting from systemic lupus erythematosus.

otulipenia is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the immune system. It is characterized by neonatal onset of recurrent fever, erythematous rash with painful nodules, painful joints, and lipodystrophy. The disease has a material basis in homozygous loss-of-function mutations in the OTULIN gene, which encodes a deubiquitinase with linear linkage specificity on chromosome 5p15.
This is a type of myeloid neoplasm that is characterized by the formation of abnormal fusion genes that encode constitutively activated tyrosine kinases.

Myeloid and lymphoid neoplasms associated with PDGFRA rearrangement is a rare type of cancer that affects the bone marrow and blood cells. It is characterized by abnormalities in the PDGFRA gene, which leads to the formation of FIP1L1-PDGFRA fusion transcripts. These transcripts can cause overproduction of certain proteins, leading to excessive cell growth and cancer development. Symptoms may include fever, fatigue, and an increased number of white blood cells in the blood. Treatment options depend on the specific type of cancer and the extent of disease, but may include chemotherapy, radiation therapy, or stem cell transplantation.

Myeloid and lymphoid neoplasms associated with PDGFRB rearrangement is a type of cancer that affects the bone marrow and blood cells. It is characterized by the presence of fusion genes in these cells, specifically involving the PDGFRA, PDGFRB, and FGFR1 genes. This leads to abnormalities in the production of certain proteins involved in cell growth and differentiation, which can result in the development of cancerous cells. It is often associated with a condition called eosinophilia, which is characterized by an increase in white blood cells called eosinophils.

myeloid and lymphoid neoplasms associated with fgfr1 abnormalities is a type of cancer that affects the bone marrow, where white blood cells are produced. It is characterized by an overproduction of eosinophils, which are a type of white blood cell, as well as abnormalities in the PDGFRA, PDGFRB and FGFR1 genes. These genetic abnormalities can lead to the formation of tumors in the bone marrow and other parts of the body. It is also associated with a condition called "eosinophilia-associated syndromes," which can cause eosinophilia, or an elevated number of eosinophils in the blood.

Tricuspid atresia is a congenital heart defect in which the tricuspid valve of the heart does not develop properly or is completely absent. It occurs due to abnormal development during fetal life and can present with different severity levels, from mild to severe.
The term "atresia" refers to the absence of a structure or organ in the body. In this case, it pertains to the tricuspid valve, which is one of the four heart valves that regulate blood flow between the atria and ventricles of the heart. As a result, tricuspid atresia can lead to various complications such as cyanosis (a blueish discoloration of the skin and mucous membranes caused by low oxygen levels), heart failure, and an increased risk of infections due to stunted growth or other issues.
Tricuspid atresia is typically diagnosed during infancy or early childhood through physical examination, echocardiogram, or other imaging tests. Treatment options may include surgical interventions, such as the Fontan procedure, which reroutes blood flow from the right ventricle to the lungs without the need for a permanent pacemaker.

Yes, you are correct. Normophosphatemic familial tumoral calcinosis is a type of calcinosis characterized by the deposition of calcium deposits in soft tissues and organs, particularly in the joints and kidneys. It is caused by an imbalance in phosphate metabolism and can be inherited or acquired. It is important to note that this condition can cause severe pain, joint stiffness, and kidney problems if left untreated.

esophageal atresia tracheoesophageal fistula is a type of gastrointestinal system disease. It is characterized by abnormal development of the esophagus and trachea, where the upper esophagus does not connect to the lower esophagus and stomach, and may also include tracheoesophageal fistula, which allows fluids from the esophagus to get into the airways and interfere with breathing. This condition has exact synonyms such as esophageal atresia and/or tracheoesophageal fistula, as well as tracheoesophageal fistula with or without esophageal atresia.

Thiopurine S-methyltransferase deficiency, also known as TPMT deficiency, is an inherited metabolic disorder characterized by a significantly reduced activity of the enzyme thiopurine S-methyltransferase. This enzyme helps the body process drugs called thiopurines, which are commonly used to treat various medical conditions, including cancer and autoimmune diseases. When individuals with TPMT deficiency receive thiopurines as part of their treatment regimen, they are at a higher risk of experiencing adverse side effects due to the decreased ability of the enzyme to metabolize these drugs.

Bladder exstrophy, epispadias, and cloacal exstrophy are all types of congenital disorders that affect the development of various organs in a person's body. These disorders can occur due to genetic factors or other underlying causes.

Exstrophy-epispadias complex is a specific type of bladder exstrophy, which involves the underdevelopment of the normal covering around the urinary tract (urogenital sinus) and the urethra, leading to the exposure of these structures in the abdomen. Epispadias, on the other hand, is a defect involving the opening of the urethra on the dorsum (back) of the penis or the perineum. Cloacal exstrophy occurs when the anus and genitals do not develop properly, leading to a fusion of the anal and genital openings.

These disorders can have significant impacts on a person's life, including difficulties with urination, sexual function, and overall quality of life. Treatment options for bladder exstrophy may include surgery, physical therapy, and specialized care from healthcare professionals. It is important to work closely with medical experts to manage the symptoms and complications associated with these disorders effectively.

Bladder exstrophy is a rare congenital birth defect that affects the development of the urinary bladder. It occurs when the wall of the bladder does not form properly, causing the bladder to protrude outwards through an opening in the abdominal wall. This results in the exposure of the urinary tract and can lead to a range of complications if left untreated.

Bladder exstrophy is typically diagnosed shortly after birth and requires prompt surgical intervention to correct the defect. The surgery involves repositioning the bladder, repairing the abdominal wall, and closing the opening in the abdomen. In some cases, additional surgeries may be necessary to address any remaining issues or complications.

With proper treatment and care, individuals with bladder exstrophy can lead relatively normal lives. However, they will require ongoing monitoring and management of their condition throughout their lifetime, including regular follow-up appointments with a healthcare provider and adherence to specific dietary and hygiene guidelines.

Overall, while bladder exstrophy is a challenging condition, advances in medical technology and surgical techniques have made it possible for many affected individuals to lead fulfilling lives with proper care and management.

Cloacal exstrophy is a type of birth defect that occurs when the baby's genitals, bladder, and bowel do not develop properly. It is considered to be a complex condition because it involves multiple parts of the body and can lead to various complications if left untreated. The term "cloacal exstrophy" refers specifically to a defect in the urethra, bladder, and bowel. Epispadias is a congenital anomaly involving the urinary meatus and urethral plate that leads to an abnormal opening of the urethra on the dorsum of the penis. The cloacal exstrophy complex is characterized by a combination of these two conditions, along with other potential defects in the genital, urinary, and gastrointestinal systems. This type of birth defect can be quite challenging to manage and may require a multidisciplinary approach involving pediatric surgeons, urologists, gynecologists, and other specialists.

Yes, that is correct. Meningococcal meningitis is a type of bacterial meningitis caused by the Neisseria meningitidis bacterium. It is an inflammation of the membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord, which can be life-threatening if not treated promptly and effectively. Symptoms may include fever, headache, stiff neck, vomiting, and a rash or purple spots on the skin. It is important to seek medical attention immediately if these symptoms are present. Is there anything else you would like to know about meningococcal meningitis?

Hepatic veno-occlusive disease (VOD) is a type of hepatic vascular disease that affects the small blood vessels within the liver. It is characterized by obstruction or narrowing of these vessels, which can lead to decreased blood flow and increased pressure in the liver. VOD can occur as a complication of certain medical treatments, such as chemotherapy for cancer patients, or it can be idiopathic (meaning the cause is unknown). Symptoms may include abdominal pain, swelling, jaundice, and fatigue. Diagnosis typically involves imaging studies such as ultrasound, CT scan, or MRI to visualize the liver and its blood vessels. Treatment options may include medications to improve blood flow (such as pentoxifylline), dietary changes, and in some cases, liver transplantation.

Mucositis is a gastrointestinal system disease that affects the mucous membranes lining the digestive tract. It can cause pain and inflammation, and may lead to the formation of ulcers in the affected areas. Mucositis can be caused by a variety of factors, including infections, autoimmune disorders, and certain medications. Treatment options for mucositis may include medications to reduce inflammation and pain, as well as dietary changes and rest. In severe cases, hospitalization may be necessary.
Haemophilus meningitis is a type of bacterial meningitis that has material basis in Haemophilus influenzae infection.

Zika virus congenital syndrome is a type of physical disorder characterized by microcephaly, craniofacial disproportion, spasticity, seizures, irritability and brainstem dysfunction including feeding difficulties, ocular abnormalities, and findings on neuroimaging such as calcifications, cortical disorders, ventriculomegaly. It is caused by the acquisition of Zika virus in utero.

Pharc syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects many systems of the body, including the peripheral nervous system, inner ear, cerebellum, and eye. It is caused by mutations in the PMP22 gene, which provides instructions for making a protein called peripheral myelin protein 22. The loss of this protein leads to degeneration of the nerves that control movement and sensation in the hands and feet. In addition to polyneuropathy, Pharc syndrome can also cause hearing loss, cerebellar ataxia, retinitis pigmentosa, and early-onset cataracts.

Mixed fibrolamellar hepatocellular carcinoma is a type of cancer that arises from the liver. It is characterized by the presence of both pure fibrolamellar hepatocellular carcinoma and conventional hepatocellular carcinoma components.
That is correct. Medullary colon carcinoma is a type of colon carcinoma that is characterized by a solid growth pattern.

mixed mucinous and nonmucinous bronchioloalveolar adenocarcinoma is a subtype of bronchiolo alveolar adenocarcinoma, characterized by the presence of both mucin-producing (mucinous) and non-mucin-producing (nonmucinous) components. This type of cancer may have a more aggressive behavior than other subtypes of bronchioloalveolar adenocarcinoma, and is often associated with poorer prognosis.
It is also known as indeterminate bronchioloalveolar carcinoma because it is difficult to determine the specific type of cancer based on the appearance of the tumor cells under a microscope.

mucinous bronchioloalveolar adenocarcinoma is a type of cancer that affects the lungs. It is characterized by the presence of mucin in the tumor cells and the growth of tall columnar cells along alveolar walls without stromal invasion.

I understand that you are providing information about nonmucinous bronchioloalveolar adenocarcinoma, which is a type of bronchiolo alveolar adenocarcinoma. Nonmucinous bronchioloalveolar adenocarcinoma is defined as a bronchiolo-alveolar adenocarcinoma characterized by cells with cuboidal or columnar morphology and eosinophilic or clear cytoplasm, which shows Clara cell or type 2 pneumocyte differentiation. Is there anything else I can help you with?

Chronic neutrophilic leukemia (CNL) is a type of chronic leukemia that is characterized by an abnormal increase in white blood cells, specifically neutrophils. It occurs when the body produces too many white blood cells, particularly neutrophils, which are important for fighting off infections. CNL can be caused by various factors, including genetic mutations, exposure to certain chemicals or radiation, and viral infections.

CNL is different from other types of leukemia because it does not involve the Philadelphia chromosome or the BCR/ABL fusion gene. Instead, it is characterized by a high number of normal-appearing neutrophils in the blood, bone marrow, and other tissues.

Treatment for CNL usually involves chemotherapy to reduce the number of white blood cells in the body. In some cases, a bone marrow transplant may be recommended to replace the damaged bone marrow with healthy stem cells. Regular monitoring of blood cell counts and bone marrow function is essential to ensure that the disease does not return or worsen.

It's important to note that CNL can be a serious condition, but with proper treatment, it can be managed effectively. If you or someone you know has been diagnosed with CNL, it's crucial to work closely with a healthcare professional to develop an appropriate treatment plan.

Chronic Myelomonocytic Leukemia (CMML) is a type of chronic leukemia characterized by an excess of monocytes in the bone marrow and an increase in the blood. It is also known for its variable degrees of dysplasia, which is an abnormality in the formation of blood cells. Unlike other forms of leukemia, CMML does not involve a lack of normal white blood cells. Instead, it is characterized by the build-up of immature granulocytes in the bone marrow and blood.

Malignant hemangioma is a type of cancer that arises from the blood vessels, specifically the endothelial cells that line them. It is also known as vascular sarcoma or vascular cancer. These tumors can grow quickly and may invade nearby tissues or spread to other parts of the body. They are typically treated with surgery or radiation therapy, but chemotherapy may also be used in some cases.

Malignant epithelioid hemangioendothelioma is a type of malignant tumor that originates from the blood vessels. It is characterized by the presence of epithelioid endothelial cells, which are arranged in cords and nests that are embedded in a myxoid to hyalinized stroma. This type of hemangioma is aggressive and has a poor prognosis.

PTEN hamartoma tumor syndrome is a type of genetic disorder that is caused by mutations in the PTEN gene. It is characterized by the presence of benign tumors, typically on the skin or inside the digestive tract, and other developmental abnormalities. The condition can also be associated with an increased risk of certain types of cancer.

Relapsed refractory diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (RRDLBCL) is a type of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma that has relapsed or become resistant to previous treatment. It is characterized by the presence of large B cells, which are a type of white blood cell, and can be found in various parts of the body, including the lymph nodes, bone marrow, and spleen. RRDLBCL is an aggressive form of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma that can progress quickly and may require immediate treatment. Symptoms can include weight loss, fever, night sweats, fatigue, and swollen lymph nodes.

Superior semicircular canal dehiscence is an inner ear disease characterized by a dehiscence in the bone overlying the superior semicircular canal, which can lead to symptoms such as pressure or sound-induced vertigo, bone conduction hyperacusis, and pulsatile tinnitus. It has exact synonyms like canal dehiscence syndrome, superior canal dehiscence, superior canal syndrome, superior semicircular canal dehiscence syndrome, and third mobile window syndrome.

Carey-Fineman-Ziter syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by several distinctive features. These include hypotonia, Moebius sequence, Pierre Robin complex, delayed motor milestones, and failure to thrive. One of the main symptoms is ptosis (drooping eyelids) which occurs due to weakness in the muscles responsible for raising the eyelids. The syndrome is named after its three discoverers: Dr. Carey, Dr. Fineman, and Dr. Ziter.

Marinesco-Sjogren Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple organ systems in the body. It is characterized by congenital cataracts, cerebellar ataxia, progressive muscle weakness due to myopathy, and delayed psychomotor development. The syndrome is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a child must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder. It is also sometimes referred to as Marinesco-Garland Syndrome or Oligophrenic cerebello-lental degeneration.

Mandibulofacial dysostosis Guion Almeida type, also known as MFDM syndrome, is a genetic disorder that affects the development of the face and skull. It is characterized by progressive microcephaly (small head size), micrognathia (small jaw), microtia (small ear), dysplastic ears, preauricular skin tags, speech delay, significant developmental delay, midface and malar hypoplasia (underdevelopment of the cheekbones and bony structures in the face).

This disorder is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that a single copy of the gene can be passed down from one generation to another. It is also known as mandibulofacial dysostosis with microcephaly or mandibulofacial dysostosis-microcephaly syndrome.

Congenital muscular dystrophy with cataracts and intellectual disability is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by the onset of progressive muscle weakness in early childhood. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the INPP5K gene (607875) located on chromosome 17p13.

infantile histiocytoid cardiomyopathy is a type of monogenic disease.
infantile histiocytoid cardiomyopathy is a type of intrinsic cardiomyopathy.
infantile histiocytoid cardiomyopathy is a type of something that at least disease has basis in some gene.
infantile histiocytoid cardiomyopathy has definition An intrinsic cardiomyopathy characterized by the presence of characteristic pale granular foamy histiocyte-like cells within the myocardium and has_material_basis_in a mutation in the gene encoding mitochondrial cytochrome b.
Colorectal carcinoma is a type of colorectal cancer that arises from the colon or rectum and invades through the muscularis mucosa into the submucosa.

Bilateral renal agenesis is a condition in which both kidneys are not present at birth. It can occur alone or as part of Potter's Syndrome, which also involves heart defects and low levels of amniotic fluid.

Peter's Plus Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by several distinctive features, including anterior chamber eye anomalies, short limbs with broad distal extremities, characteristic facial features, cleft lip/palate, and variable developmental delay or intellectual disability. It is also known as Krause-Kivlin Syndrome, Peters Anomaly-Short Limb Dwarfism Syndrome, and Peters-Plus Syndrome.

Adenoid cystic carcinoma is a type of cancer that originates in the salivary glands. It typically affects the parotid, submandibular and sublingual glands, but can also occur in other salivary gland sites. The tumor is made up of both epithelial and stromal cells, with a characteristic pattern of hyalinized or mucinous stroma separating or surrounded by nests or cords of small epithelial cells.

renal hypoplasia is a type of kidney disease that occurs when one or both kidneys fail to develop properly during fetal development. This can result in abnormally small kidneys with normal morphology and reduced number of nephrons, which can lead to a variety of problems related to the filtration and excretion of waste products from the blood.
Renal hypoplasia can be caused by a variety of factors, including genetic defects, exposure to certain drugs or chemicals, infections, and other medical conditions. It is often diagnosed through a combination of physical examination, imaging studies (such as ultrasound or CT scan), and blood tests that measure kidney function. Treatment options for renal hypoplasia depend on the underlying cause and severity of the condition, but may include medications to manage symptoms, dietary changes, and close monitoring by a healthcare professional.

cakut is a medical condition characterized by abnormalities in the development of the kidneys and/or urinary tract. These abnormalities can include vesicoureteral reflux, which occurs when urine flows back up into the kidneys. Cakut is also known as congenital anomalies of the kidney and urinary tract or renal or urinary tract malformation. It can lead to a variety of symptoms such as blood in the urine, pain in the abdomen or flank area, and frequent urination. It is important for those with cakut to receive proper medical care and treatment to manage their condition.

cakut1 is a type of cakut that has a definition as having a heterozygous mutation in the DSTYK gene on chromosome 1q32. It also has an exact synonym, Congenital anomalies of the kidney and urinary tract 1.

Cakut2 is a medical condition that affects the kidneys and urinary tract. It is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the TBX18 gene on chromosome 6q14. The condition is also known as Congenital Anomalies of the Kidney and Urinary Tract 2 (CAKUT 2).

:metabolic_dysfunction_associated_steatotic_liver_disease rdfs:subClassOf :steatotic_liver_disease ;
    :has_definition """A steatotic liver disease characterized by at least one of five cardiometabolic risk factors (adjusted for age, sex and ethnicity), alcohol consumption below 140g/week (female) or 210g/week (male), and no other discernible cause. The five cardiometabolic risk factors are:
(1) Body mass index ≥ 25 kg/m2 (adult), 23 kg/m2 (adult Asian), or 85th percentile (pediatric); waist circumference > 94 cm (adult male), 80 cm (adult female), or 95th percentile (pediatric); or ethnicity adjusted equivalents.
(2) Fasting serum glucose ≥ 5.6 mmol/L, 2-hr post-load glucose levels ≥ 7.8 mmol/L, glycated hemoglobin (HbA1c) ≥ 5.7% (39 mmol/L), type 2 diabetes, treatment for type 2 diabetes, previously diagnosed or treated type 2 diabetes (pediatric only), or serum glucose ≥ 11.1 mmol/L (pediatric only).
(3) Blood pressure ≥ lower of 130/85 mmHg or 95th percentile (age < 13 years), or 130/85 mmHg (age ≥ 13 years); or specific hypertensive drug treatment.
(4) Plasma triglycerides ≥ 1.15 mmol/L (age < 10 years) or 1.70 mmol/L (age ≥ 10 years); or lipid lowering treatment.
(5) Plasma high-density lipoprotein cholesterol ≤ 1.0 mmol/L (adult male, pediatric) or 1.3 mmol/L (adult female); or lipid lowering treatment.""" ;

text: Yes, metabolic dysfunction associated steatotic liver disease (MAFLD) is a type of non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD), characterized by at least one of five cardiometabolic risk factors. These risk factors include a body mass index (BMI) of 25 kg/m2 or higher, waist circumference greater than 94 cm in adult males, or 80 cm in adult females, ethnicity-adjusted equivalents, fasting serum glucose levels of 5.6 mmol/L or higher, two-hour post-load glucose levels of 7.8 mmol/L or higher, glycated hemoglobin (HbA1c) of 5.7% or higher, and the presence of type 2 diabetes, previous diagnosis or treatment of type 2 diabetes, or serum glucose levels of 11.1 mmol/L or higher in pediatric patients. MAFLD is also associated with other conditions like hypertension and dyslipidemia. It is essential to identify and manage these risk factors early on to prevent the progression of MAFLD to more severe forms of liver disease.

Sideroblastic anemia with B cell immunodeficiency, periodic fevers and developmental delay is a rare genetic disorder that affects the production of red blood cells. It is caused by mutations in the TRNT1 gene on chromosome 3p26 and can be inherited in an autosomal recessive manner. The disorder is characterized by severe sideroblastic anemia in the neonatal period or infancy, developmental delay, periodic fevers, and immune system dysfunction.

Primary mediastinal B-cell lymphoma (PMBCL) is a type of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma. It is characterized by the diffuse proliferation of medium to large B cells associated with sclerosis in the mediastinum, which is the area between the lungs. PMBCL can also be referred to as large cell lymphoma of the mediastinum, mediatinal diffuse large-cell lym

Nodal Marginal Zone Lymphoma (NMZL) is a type of lymphoma that affects the lymph nodes. It's characterized by having a marginal zone-like appearance, which is similar to the appearance of lymph nodes involved in extranodal or splenic types of marginal zone lymphomas. However, it doesn't have any evidence of extranodal or splenic disease.

Polycystic kidney disease 4, also known as PKD4, is a type of autosomal recessive polycystic kidney disease. This means that it is caused by the mutation of the PKD4 gene and can be inherited from both parents who are carriers of the mutated gene. Polycystic kidney disease 4 is characterized by the growth of multiple cysts in the kidneys, which can lead to a decrease in kidney function over time.

Punctate palmoplantar keratoderma type II, also known as palmoplantar keratodermia linearis, is a genetic skin disorder that affects the palms of the hands and soles of the feet. It is characterized by the formation of small, sharp, horn-like projections on the skin's surface, which can cause discomfort and pain when walking or standing for extended periods.
Punctate palmoplantar keratoderma type II is an autosomal dominant inherited disease, meaning that it can be passed down through families and tends to affect multiple generations. It typically begins in childhood or adolescence and can last a lifetime if left untreated. Treatment options include topical steroids, retinoids, and keratolytics, but the progression of the disease may still occur despite treatment.

Punctate palmoplantar keratoderma type I, also known as punctate palmoplantar keratoderma type 1A and 1B, is a skin condition characterized by multiple, hyperkeratotic (horn-like) centrally indented papules that develop in early adolescence or later on the palms of hands and soles of feet. These papules are irregularly distributed and have a "punctate" appearance due to their small size and raised, depressed center. It is a non-contagious, genetic condition that affects individuals of all ages but is more common in adolescents and young adults.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 8 (DEE8) is a type of X-linked recessive disease that affects brain development and causes severe seizures in infants. It is characterized by onset before the age of two, severe developmental delay, and sometimes hyperekplexia, which has a material basis in the X-linked recessive inheritance of a mutation in the ARHGEF9 gene located on chromosome Xq22.1.
DEE8 is also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 8 (EIEE8) and has the same meaning as developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 8.

That is correct, duodenal atresia is a type of congenital intestinal obstruction that occurs due to the absence or complete closure of a portion of the lumen of the duodenum. It can cause problems with the absorption of nutrients and fluids, leading to malnutrition if not properly diagnosed and treated. Treatment options for duodenal atresia depend on the severity of the condition and may include surgery or other medical interventions.

Lysosomal acid lipase deficiency is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to break down fats (lipids). It is caused by mutations in the LIPA gene, which is located on chromosome 10q23.31. This leads to an accumulation of cholesteryl esters and triglycerides within various organs, including the liver, spleen, and lungs. It can also cause dyslipidemia, which is a condition characterized by abnormal levels of lipids in the blood. Symptoms can include fatigue, weakness, and joint pain. Lysosomal acid lipase deficiency is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. It is also known as LAL deficiency or LAL-D.

Primary spontaneous pneumothorax (PSP) is a medical condition characterized by the sudden collapse of a lung due to the accumulation of air in the space between the lungs and the chest wall. PSP can be life-threatening if not treated promptly, as it can lead to decreased oxygenation of the blood and respiratory failure.

Symptoms of PSP may include shortness of breath, sharp pain in the chest, cough, and rapid heart rate. Diagnosis is usually made through a combination of physical examination, chest X-rays, and lung function tests. Treatment options for PSP include chest tube insertion to remove air from the pleural space, surgical repair of the damaged lung, or lung transplantation in severe cases.

It is important to seek medical attention immediately if you suspect that you have PSP, as prompt treatment can significantly improve outcomes and prevent complications.

Dystransthyretinemic hyperthyroxinemia is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which means that it can be passed down through genes from one generation to the next. It is characterized by an increased affinity for thyroxine (T4) by transthyretin in clinically euthyroid individuals and has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the TTR gene on chromosome 18q12.

Pseudohypoparathyroidism type Ia is a condition characterized by resistance to the parathyroid hormone (PTH) resulting in low levels of calcium in the blood (hypocalcemia), high levels of phosphorus in the blood (hyperphosphatemia), and elevated PTH levels. It is caused by mutations that alter the methylation pattern of GNAS on chromosome 20q13.32, resulting in a gain of function or loss of function in the alpha-subunit of the receptor for PTH.
epidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma is a type of palmoplantar keratosis characterized by hyperkeratosis on the surface of the palms and soles.

Autosomal dominant dystrophic epidermolysis bullosa is a type of epidermolysis bullosa dystrophica that is characterized by recurrent blistering at the level of the lamina densa, which is caused by minor trauma and primarily affects the nails, hands, feet, knees, and elbows. This condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner through mutations in the COL7A1 gene, which encodes a protein that assists with the assembly of type VII collagen.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) is a progressive neurodegenerative disease that affects nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord, leading to muscle weakness and atrophy. There are different types of ALS, and one type is called Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis Type 23, which is characterized by a genetic mutation in the ANXA11 gene on chromosome 10q22. This specific type of ALS has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the ANXA11 gene on chromosome 10q22.

autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder 56 is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder.
autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder 56 is a type of something that at least has material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.
autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder 56 has definition An autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder that is characterized by global developmental delay, intellectual disability and in most cases hypotonia, delayed walking, poor fine motor skills, and poor or absent speech that has_material_basis_in heterozygous mutation in the CLTC gene on chromosome 17q23..
autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder 56 has exact synonym autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder-56.
autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder 56 has exact synonym autosomal dominant mental retardation 56.

Autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder 55, also known as ADIDD-55, is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder characterized by onset of myoclonic seizures in the first years of life, global developmental delay, intellectual disability, speech delay and ataxic gait that has material basis in heterozygous mutation in the NUS1 gene on chromosome 6q22. It is also known as autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder-55 with seizures and autosomal dominant mental retardation 55.

Autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder 53, also known as autosomal dominant mental retardation 53, is a type of intellectual developmental disorder that has a genetic basis. It is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the CAMK2A gene on chromosome 5q32.

Autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder 54, also known as autosomal dominant mental retardation 54, is a type of intellectual developmental disorder. It is characterized by a lack of cognitive abilities that can be attributed to a genetic mutation in the CAMK2B gene on chromosome 7p13. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in this gene and can affect an individual's physical development, speech, and behavior. It is important for individuals with autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder 54 to receive proper medical care and support from specialists in order to manage their symptoms effectively.

Autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder 52 (ADIDD52) is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder that is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the ASH1L gene on chromosome 1q22. It has been referred to as autosomal dominant mental retardation 52. This disorder affects brain development and can result in intellectual and developmental problems for affected individuals.

Autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder 51 (ADIDD51) is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder. It is characterized by having a heterozygous mutation in the KMT5B gene on chromosome 11q13. This genetic variation can lead to an array of neurological and cognitive problems, such as developmental delays, intellectual disability, motor skills issues, speech difficulties, and behavioral challenges.

ADIDD51 is also known by its exact synonym, autosomal dominant mental retardation 51 (ADMR51). These terms are used to describe individuals who have been affected by a specific genetic abnormality that can significantly impact their overall development and well-being.

It is important for individuals with ADIDD51, as well as their families and caregivers, to seek out proper medical and therapeutic support to manage the challenges associated with this condition. This may include working with specialized healthcare professionals who can help develop individualized treatment plans and provide guidance on best practices for coping with the unique needs of those affected by ADIDD51.

Autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder 50, also known as autosomal dominant mental retardation 50, is a type of intellectual disability that is caused by a mutation in the NAA15 gene on chromosome 4q31. This condition is characterized by behavioral abnormalities and can impact an individual's cognitive functioning and development.

Clark-Baraitser syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by intellectual and developmental delays. It is caused by a mutation in the TRIP12 gene, which is located on chromosome 2q36. The exact synonyms for this condition include Baraitser syndrome, CLABARS, autosomal dominant intellectual disability 49, and autosomal dominant mental retardation 49.

Autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder 48 (ADMD 48) is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder. It has a definition as an autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the RAC1 gene on chromosome 7p22. Additionally, it has an exact synonym of Autosomal dominant mental retardation 48 (ADMR 48).

Autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder 45, also known as autosomal dominant mental retardation 45, is a type of intellectual developmental disorder that is characterized by a heterozygous mutation in the CIC gene on chromosome 19q13. This disorder has a material basis in the brain and can affect an individual's cognitive functioning, social interactions, and adaptive behaviors. It is important to note that this is just one of several types of intellectual developmental disorders, which are a class of neurodevelopmental disabilities that can occur during infancy or childhood and have lasting impacts on an individual's cognitive and behavioral functioning.

autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder 46 is a type of autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder. It has a definition as an autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder that has_material_basis_in heterozygous mutation in the KCNQ5 gene on chromosome 6q14. Additionally, it has an exact synonym of autosomal dominant mental retardation 46.

Autosomal dominant intellectual developmental disorder 47, also known as autosomal dominant mental retardation 47, is a type of intellectual developmental disorder that has a genetic basis. Specifically, it is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the STAG1 gene on chromosome 3q22.

autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder 61 is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder that has_material_basis_in homozygous mutation in the RUN and SH3 domain containing 2 gene (RUSC2) on chromosome 9p13.
autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder 61 is also known as Alwadei syndrome, autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder-61, and autosomal recessive mental retardation 61.

Non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 106, also known as MRX106 and X-linked mental retardation 106, is a type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability that has a genetic basis in hemizygous mutations on the OGT gene located on chromosome Xq13.1.

Syndromic X-linked mental retardation 35 (also known as SXMR35) is a type of intellectual disability that is characterized by the presence of multiple congenital anomalies, which are physical abnormalities that occur during fetal development. These anomalies often involve the brain and spinal cord, and can include conditions such as hydrocephalus, microcephaly, spina bifida, and cleft lip/palate. SXMR35 is inherited in an X-linked recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to be affected by the disorder. The RPL10 gene on chromosome Xq28 is known to be associated with SXMR35.

Syndromic X-linked mental retardation, Hough type (SYX2) is a specific form of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. It is characterized by developmental delays, intellectual disability, speech and language difficulties, and early-onset seizures. The condition has a material basis in either hemizygous or heterozygous mutations in the CNKSR2 gene located on the Xp22 chromosome region.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 3b is a condition where the enamel production is disrupted, resulting in thin or missing teeth. It is caused by genetic mutations and can be inherited from one or both parents.

Galloway-Mowat syndrome 2 is a type of rare genetic disorder that affects the development of skin, hair, nails and teeth. It is inherited in an X-linked recessive pattern, which means that it requires the presence of two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) for the affected individual to develop the condition. The syndrome is caused by a mutation in the LAGE3 gene, which is located on the X chromosome at position q28. It affects males more commonly than females due to the way that the X chromosome is inherited.
Galloway-Mowat syndrome 2 can cause various physical abnormalities such as hypertelorism (a broad nasal bridge), brachydactyly (shortened fingers and toes), and distinctive facial features. It also affects the teeth, causing conical teeth or agenesis of permanent teeth.
Overall, Galloway-Mowat syndrome 2 is a rare condition that can cause a range of physical and dental abnormalities. With proper care and treatment, individuals with this syndrome can lead healthy lives.
galloway mowat syndrome 3 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the OSGEP gene on chromosome 14q11.
Galloway-Mowat syndrome 4 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the skin, hair, and nails. It is caused by mutations in the TP53RK gene on chromosome 20q13.

Galloway-Mowat syndrome 5, also known as TPRKB deficiency, is a rare genetic disorder that is characterized by the lack of functional TPRKB protein. This protein is essential for maintaining the structural integrity and stability of the cytoskeleton in the inner ear, which can lead to various hearing and balance problems. Additionally, TPRKB deficiency has been linked to other health issues such as intellectual disability, seizures, and abnormal facial features. It is caused by a homozygous mutation in the TPRKB gene on chromosome 2p13.

Erythrokeratodermia variabilis et progressiva 2 is a specific type of erythrokeratodermia variabilis that is characterized by persistent plaque-like or generalized hyperkeratosis and transient red patches of variable size, shape, and location. It is also described as having a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding connexin-30.3 (GJB4) on chromosome 1p34.

Erythrokeratodermia variabilis et progressiva 3, also known as EKV-III, is a type of autosomal dominant skin disorder characterized by the development of hyperpigmentation and scaling at friction sites in childhood. The disorder's progression leads to near-confluent corrugated hyperkeratosis, palmoplantar keratoderma, and transient figurate erythema. It is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding connexin-43 (GJA1) on chromosome 6q22.

Erythrokeratodermia variabilis et progressiva 4 is a type of erythrokeratodermia variabilis that has severe symptoms, primarily affecting the face and genitals. It also causes thickened, red, and scaly skin on the hands and feet. This condition is caused by a compound heterozygous mutation in the KDSR gene on chromosome 18q21.

Erythrokeratodermia variabilis et progressiva 5 is a type of skin condition that affects the epidermal layer and is characterized by a rash on the palms, soles, and fingers. It is caused by mutations in the KRT83 gene and is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern.

spastic ataxia 8 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the NKX6-2 gene on chromosome 8q21. It is characterized by onset of primarily motor dysfunction within the first year of life.

The Meckel Syndrome is a group of disorders that are passed down through families. It occurs when someone inherits two copies of the faulty gene, one from each parent. There are three types of Meckel Syndrome: Type 1, Type 2 and Type 3. Each type has its own set of physical features and symptoms.

Orofaciodigital syndrome XVI is a genetic disorder that affects the development of the facial and digital features. It is caused by mutations in the TMEM107 gene, which is located on chromosome 17p13. This condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder. Orofaciodigital syndrome XVI can cause a variety of physical abnormalities, including cleft lip and palate, polydactyly (extra fingers or toes), and distinctive facial features such as a small jaw, widely spaced eyes, and a thin mouth.

Meier-Gorlin syndrome 8, also known as type 2 osteogenesis imperfecta, is a genetic disorder characterized by weak bones that are prone to fractures. It is caused by mutations in the MCM5 gene on chromosome 22q12. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder.

Perrault syndrome 6, also known as Eral1-related sensorineural hearing loss, is a type of genetic disorder characterized by sensorineural deafness in both males and females. In addition to the hearing impairment, females with this condition may experience ovarian dysgenesis, which can result in amenorrhea (absence of menstruation) and infertility.
Perrault syndrome 6 is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that to develop the condition, a person must have two copies of the faulty gene, one from each parent. The gene responsible for this disorder is ERAL1, located on chromosome 17q11.

autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis 13 is a type of autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis, which is a type of disease that occurs due to an abnormality in prenatal development or at birth. This specific condition is characterized by lamellar ichthyosis, ectropion, eclabium and hyperkeratosis, all of which are caused by a mutation in the SDR9C7 gene on chromosome 12q13.

autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis 14 is a type of autosomal recessive congenital ichthyosis, which is characterized by lamellar ichthyosis, ectropion, eclabium and hyperkeratosis. These symptoms are caused by a mutation in the SULT2B1 gene on chromosome 19q13.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 25 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia that is characterized by a gradual loss of coordination and balance. It is caused by a mutation in the ATG5 gene on chromosome 6q21. The condition has an exact synonym of SCAR25.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 26 (SCAR26) is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia that is characterized by progressive loss of coordination and balance. It is caused by compound heterozygous mutations in the XRCC1 gene, which is located on chromosome 19q13. SCAR26 is one of several forms of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, which are a group of genetic disorders that affect the cerebellum and can cause problems with balance, coordination, and muscle control. Other examples include cerebellar ataxias caused by mutations in the Ataxin-2 gene or the Ataxin-3 gene.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 106 (ARD106) is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness, which means it is caused by the inheritance of two copies of a defective gene from each parent. In this case, the mutation is located in the EPS8L2 gene on chromosome 11p15.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 107, also known as DFNB34, is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness. It is caused by mutations in the WBP2 gene located on chromosome 17q25. This condition affects the ability to hear and can lead to significant hearing loss or even complete deafness if not treated early on.

Autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness 108 is a type of autosomal recessive nonsyndromic deafness, which means it's caused by the inheritance of two copies of a mutated gene on one of the autosomes (non-sex chromosomes). The ROR1 gene on chromosome 1p31 has been identified as the cause of this specific type of deafness.
exudative vitreoretinopathy 7 is a type of exudative vitreoretinopathy that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the CTNNB1 gene on chromosome 3p22.1. It is also known as EVR7.

Nephrotic syndrome type 14 is a form of autosomal recessive kidney disease. It is caused by mutations in the SGPL1 gene on chromosome 10q21, which encodes the sphingosine-1-phosphate lyase enzyme. These mutations lead to a deficiency of this enzyme, causing an imbalance in the levels of sphingosine-1-phosphate and other molecules in the kidneys. This can result in symptoms such as proteinuria, edema, and decreased urine concentration. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that to develop the disease, a person must have two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent).

Primary Ciliary Dyskinesia (PCD) is a rare, genetic disorder that affects the cilia, which are hair-like structures in the respiratory and reproductive systems. PCD can cause problems with breathing, movement of mucus, and infertility. There are different types of PCD, including PCD37, which is a type characterized by a homozygous mutation in the DNAH1 gene located on chromosome 3p21. It is one of the most common types of PCD, accounting for approximately 60% of cases.
Autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness 71 is a specific type of autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness that has its genetic basis in a mutation in the DMXL2 gene on chromosome 15q21.

Autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness 72 (DFNB72) is a type of autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness. It is characterized by a hearing loss that is passed down through generations of a family, and it is not caused by any specific syndrome or physical traits.

The genetic cause of DFNB72 has been identified as a heterozygous mutation in the SLC44A4 gene located on chromosome 6p21. This means that a person needs to inherit only one copy of this mutated gene in order to develop hearing loss, and it is often fully penetrant, meaning that most affected individuals will have full-blown deafness by adulthood.

It's important to note that autosomal dominant means that the condition is passed down through both males and females equally, as it is located on non-sex chromosomes (autosomes). This type of inheritance pattern can make it easier for families with a history of deafness to identify their risk and take preventative measures.

User, you are correct. Autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness 73 is a type of autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PTPRQ gene on chromosome 12q21.

Autosomal dominant nonsyndromic deafness 34 (DFNB34) is a type of autosomal dominant nonsyndromic hearing loss. It is caused by mutations in the NLRP3 gene on chromosome 1q44. The NLRP3 gene encodes a protein that plays a role in the immune response and has been linked to other diseases, such as asthma and diabetes. DFNB34 is one of the most common types of inherited hearing loss and can affect people of all ages. It is often diagnosed in childhood and may progress slowly or quickly depending on the severity of the mutation. Treatment options may include hearing aids, cochlear implants, and medications to manage symptoms such as tinnitus.

Nephrotic syndrome type 15 is a genetic disorder that affects the kidneys. It is an autosomal recessive disease, meaning that it requires the inheritance of two copies of the faulty gene to develop the condition. The MAGI2 gene on chromosome 7q21 has been identified as having a material basis in this disorder when it is homozygous or compound heterozygous. It is also known as familial nephrotic syndrome, which suggests that it can be inherited within families.

Nephrotic syndrome type 16 is a form of autosomal recessive disease that affects the kidneys. It is also known as familial nephrotic syndrome because it tends to run in families. This type of nephrotic syndrome has a genetic basis, specifically a mutation in the KANK2 gene on chromosome 19p13.

Polycystic kidney disease 5 (PKD5) is a type of autosomal recessive polycystic kidney disease. This means that it is caused by the inheritance of two copies of a mutated gene, one from each parent. The gene responsible for PKD5 is located on chromosome 3q22 and is called DZIP1L.

Multiple mitochondrial dysfunctions syndrome 5 (MMDS5) is a type of autosomal recessive disorder characterized by progressive neurologic deterioration beginning in early infancy. Affected individuals have no psychomotor development and early-onset seizures with neurologic decline and spasticity. The condition has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the iron-sulfur cluster assembly 1 gene (ISC1) on chromosome 9q21.

Joubert syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the cerebellum and brainstem. There are different types of Joubert syndrome, including type 30, which is caused by mutations in the ARMC9 gene on chromosome 2q37. The exact definition of Joubert syndrome 30 is a Joubert syndrome that has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ARMC9 gene on chromosome 2q37.

Joubert syndrome type 29, also known as Joubert syndrome with TMEM107 mutation, is a genetic disorder that occurs due to mutations in the TMEM107 gene on chromosome 17p13. This condition belongs to the category of Joubert syndrome, which is characterized by cerebellar hypoplasia (underdevelopment), abnormal cyst formation, and other related symptoms. The specific genetic changes responsible for this syndrome are not yet fully understood.
Joubert syndrome type 29 can affect various aspects of an individual's life, including cognitive function, motor skills, balance, speech, and social interactions. Early intervention and support from specialists can help manage the condition and improve the quality of life for those affected by this syndrome.

Joubert syndrome type 31 refers to a specific form of Joubert syndrome characterized by mutations in the CEP120 gene on chromosome 5q23. This genetic disorder affects the development of the cerebellum and brain, leading to symptoms such as ataxia, dystonia, oculomotor apraxia, and other neurological abnormalities. It is essential for individuals with Joubert syndrome type 31 to receive proper medical care and support to manage their condition effectively.

Joubert syndrome type 32, also known as SUFU-related Joubert syndrome, is a genetic disorder caused by mutations in the SUFU gene on chromosome 10q24. It is one of several types of Joubert syndrome, which are characterized by a distinctive appearance and abnormalities in cerebellar development.
Type 32 specifically refers to a condition where the individual has homozygous mutation in the SUFU gene, leading to an accumulation of excessive methylated cytosine residues in the genome and disruption of the normal functioning of the gene. This can result in a wide range of symptoms, including developmental delay, ataxia (difficulty with balance and coordination), hypotonia (weakness), and distinctive facial features such as a small head size, large eyes, and a flat nose.
It is important to note that the specific symptoms and severity of Joubert syndrome type 32 can vary widely between individuals, even among those with the same genetic mutation. Therefore, it is crucial for affected individuals to receive proper diagnosis and treatment from experienced healthcare professionals.

Joubert Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects brain development and can cause a range of symptoms, including unique facial features, poor balance and coordination, and vision problems. Joubert syndrome is caused by mutations in the PIBF1 gene on chromosome 13q21.
gingival fibromatosis 5 is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

Schizophrenia type 19, also known as RBM12 schizophrenia, is a genetic form of the disorder. It is characterized by a heterozygous mutation in the RBM12 gene on chromosome 20q11. This genetic variation is thought to contribute to the development of schizophrenia in some individuals.

developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 56 is a type of autosomal dominant disease.
developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 56 is a type of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy.
developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 56 is a type of something that at least has material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.
developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 56 has definition A developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by early-onset seizures in most patients, intellectual disability, and variable behavioral abnormalities that has_material_basis_in heterozygous mutation in the YWHAG gene on chromosome 7q11.
developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 56 has exact synonym DEE56.
developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 56 has exact synonym early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 56.

DEE55 is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by the onset of refractory seizures, profound intellectual disability, absence of speech, spastic quadriplegia, and dyskinetic movements. It has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PIGP gene located on chromosome 21q22. The exact synonyms for DEE55 include developmental and epileptic encephalopathy, glycosylphosphatidylinositol biosynthesis defect, and early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 55.

DEE57 refers to a type of autosomal dominant developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that is characterized by onset in the first days or months of life of refractory multifocal seizures, global developmental delay with hypotonia, variably impaired intellectual development, and poor or absent language. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the KCNT2 gene on chromosome 1q31. The exact synonyms for DEE57 are "developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 57" and "early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 57".

developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 58 (DEE58) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the brain development. It is characterized by infantile spasms, refractory seizures, global developmental delay, and impaired intellectual development. The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the NTRK2 gene on chromosome 9q21. DEE58 is also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 58 (EIEE58).
